{"title_page": "Go-Ahead Norge", "text_new": "{{Infobox company\n|name             = Go-Ahead Norge\n|logo             = \n|type             = \n|traded_as        = \n|founded          = 15 December 2019\n|founder          = \n|defunct          = \n|location_city    = [[Oslo]]\n|location_country = Norway\n|locations        = \n|area_served      = \n|key_people       = \n|industry         = [[Rail transport]]\n|products         = \n|services         = \n|revenue          = \n|operating_income = \n|net_income       = \n|num_employees    = \n|divisions        =\n|subsid           = \n|parent           = [[Go-Ahead Group]]\n|homepage         = {{url|https://go-aheadnordic.no/}}\n}}\n\n'''Go-Ahead Norge''' is a railway operator in Norway that commenced operations in December 2019. It is a subsidiary of the [[Go-Ahead Group]]. The branding used is '''Go-Ahead Nordic'''.\n\n==History==\nIn October 2018, Go-Ahead Norge was awarded an eight-year contract by the [[Norwegian Railway Directorate]] to operate the Oslo South package, consisting of three routes operated by [[Vy (transport operator)|Vy]] beating off competition from [[SJ AB|SB]] and Vy with operations commencing on 15 December 2019.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20181017203031/https://www.go-ahead.com/en/media/news/2018/go-ahead-wins-first-rail-contract-to-be-awarded-in-norway.html/ Go-Ahead wins first rail contract to be awarded in Norway] Go-Ahead Group 17 October 2018</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20190108100725/https://www.railjournal.com/passenger/main-line/go-ahead-nordic-signs-historic-contract-in-norway/ Go-Ahead Nordic signs historic contract in Norway] ''[[International Railway Journal]]'' 2 November 2018</ref><ref>Go-Ahead Nordic wins Sorlandsbanen passenger franchise ''[[Today's Railways Europe]]'' issue 276 December 2018</ref>\n\n==Services==\nGo-Ahead Norge operates services on the [[Arendal Line|Arendal]], [[J\u00e6ren Line|J\u00e6ren]] and [[S\u00f8rlandet Line]]s.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20181017171417/https://www.railwaygazette.com/news/passenger/single-view/view/go-ahead-wins-norways-first-rail-tender.html Go-Ahead wins Norway's first rail tender] ''[[Railway Gazette International]]'' 17 October 2018</ref>\n\n==Rolling stock==\nGo-Ahead Norge operates 20 [[electric multiple units]]; two [[NSB Class 69|Class 69s]], 11 [[NSB Class 72|Class 72s]] and seven [[NSB Class 73|Class 73s]]. It also operates three [[NSB El 18|El 18]] electric locomotives and 14 [[Norwegian railway carriages#Class 7 series|B7]] carriages. All are leased from Norske Tog.<ref>Go-Ahead Wins Tender ''[[Modern Railways]]'' issue 843 December 2018 page 80</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official|https://go-aheadnordic.no/}}\n\n{{Go-Ahead Group}}\n{{Railway companies of Norway}}\n\n[[Category:Go-Ahead Group companies]]\n[[Category:Railway companies of Norway]]\n[[Category:Railway companies established in 2019]]\n[[Category:2019 establishments in Norway]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox company\n|name             = Go-Ahead Norge\n|logo             = \n|type             = \n|traded_as        = \n|founded          = 15 December 2019\n|founder          = \n|defunct          = \n|location_city    = [[Oslo]]\n|location_country = Norway\n|locations        = \n|area_served      = \n|key_people       = \n|industry         = [[Rail transport]]\n|products         = \n|services         = \n|revenue          = \n|operating_income = \n|net_income       = \n|num_employees    = \n|divisions        =\n|subsid           = \n|parent           = [[Go-Ahead Group]]\n|homepage         = [https://go-aheadnordic.no/ www.go-aheadnordic.no]}}\n\n'''Go-Ahead Norge''' is a railway operator in Norway that commenced operations in December 2019. It is a subsidiary of the [[Go-Ahead Group]]. The branding used is '''Go-Ahead Nordic'''.\n\n==History==\nIn October 2018, Go-Ahead Norge was awarded an eight-year contract by the [[Norwegian Railway Directorate]] to operate the Oslo South package, consisting of three routes operated by [[Vy (transport operator)|Vy]] beating off competition from [[SJ AB|SB]] and Vy with operations commencing on 15 December 2019.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20181017203031/https://www.go-ahead.com/en/media/news/2018/go-ahead-wins-first-rail-contract-to-be-awarded-in-norway.html/ Go-Ahead wins first rail contract to be awarded in Norway] Go-Ahead Group 17 October 2018</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20190108100725/https://www.railjournal.com/passenger/main-line/go-ahead-nordic-signs-historic-contract-in-norway/ Go-Ahead Nordic signs historic contract in Norway] ''[[International Railway Journal]]'' 2 November 2018</ref><ref>Go-Ahead Nordic wins Sorlandsbanen passenger franchise ''[[Today's Railways Europe]]'' issue 276 December 2018</ref>\n\n==Services==\nGo-Ahead Norge operates services on the [[Arendal Line|Arendal]], [[J\u00e6ren Line|J\u00e6ren]] and [[S\u00f8rlandet Line]]s.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20181017171417/https://www.railwaygazette.com/news/passenger/single-view/view/go-ahead-wins-norways-first-rail-tender.html Go-Ahead wins Norway's first rail tender] ''[[Railway Gazette International]]'' 17 October 2018</ref>\n\n==Rolling stock==\nGo-Ahead Norge operates 20 [[electric multiple units]]; two [[NSB Class 69|Class 69s]], 11 [[NSB Class 72|Class 72s]] and seven [[NSB Class 73|Class 73s]]. It also operates three [[NSB El 18|El 18]] electric locomotives and 14 [[Norwegian railway carriages#Class 7 series|B7]] carriages. All are leased from Norske Tog.<ref>Go-Ahead Wins Tender ''[[Modern Railways]]'' issue 843 December 2018 page 80</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* https://go-aheadnordic.no/ Official website\n\n{{Go-Ahead Group}}\n{{Railway companies of Norway}}\n\n[[Category:Go-Ahead Group companies]]\n[[Category:Railway companies of Norway]]\n[[Category:Railway companies established in 2019]]\n[[Category:2019 establishments in Norway]]\n", "name_user": "RFBailey", "label": "safe", "comment": "external links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Go-Ahead_Norge"}
{"title_page": "Charles W. Morgan (ship)", "text_new": "{{For|the naval officer|Charles W. Morgan (naval officer)}}\n\n{{short description|American whaling ship built in 1841}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n|+''Charles W. Morgan''\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=Charles W Morgan.jpg\n|Ship caption=''Charles W. Morgan'' at [[Mystic Seaport]], [[Connecticut]]\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship country=United States\n|Ship flag={{shipboxflag|USA|1841}}\n|Ship name=\n|Ship owner=*[[Charles Waln Morgan]], 1841\u2013\n*[[J. & W. R. Wing Company]], c.1863{{spaced ndash}}c.1912<ref name=\"nrhpinv\" />\n*[[Edward Howland Robinson Green|Col. E H R Green]], c.1925\u20131941<ref name=\"nrhpinv\" />\n*Whaling Enshrined, Inc., 1941<ref name=\"nrhpinv\" />\n*[[Mystic Seaport]], 1941\u2013\n|Ship ordered=\n|Ship builder=Jethro and Zachariah Hillman, [[New Bedford, Massachusetts]]\n|Ship original cost=\n|Ship laid down=\n|Ship launched=1841\n|Ship acquired\n|Ship commissioned=\n|Ship decommissioned=\n|Ship in service=\n|Ship out of service=\n|Ship identification=*{{MMSI Number|367608930}}\n*Call sign: WDH3594\n|Ship renamed=\n|Ship fate=\n|Ship status=Museum ship\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n| Hide header=\n| Header caption=\n| Ship class= [[Full-rigged ship]]\n| Ship tonnage=351.3 [[Builder's Old Measurement#American tons burthen|(Old Tons)]]; 313.8 [[Gross Register Tonnage|(New Tons)]]<ref name = Davis>{{cite book |last=Davis |first=Lance E. |last2=Gallman |first2=Robert E. |last3=Gleiter |first3=Karen |date=1997 |url=https://www.nber.org/books/davi97-1 |title=In Pursuit of Leviathan: Technology, Institutions, Productivity, and Profits in American Whaling, 1816\u20131906 |chapter-url=https://www.nber.org/chapters/c8281.pdf |format=pdf |chapter=Chapter 6: Capital |at=Table 6.11 at p. 254 |location=Chicago |publisher=University of Chicago Press |isbn=0-226-13789-9}}  See [https://www.nber.org/chapters/c8281.pdf#page=3 p. 215] (pdf) & fn. 5 for discussion of the difference in tonnage measurements.</ref>\n| Ship length={{convert|113|ft|abbr=on}} LOA\n| Ship beam={{convert|27|ft|6|in|abbr=on}}\n| Ship draft=\n| Ship depth={{convert|17|ft|6|in|abbr=on}}\n| Ship sail plan=Double-topsail bark rig; {{convert|13000|sqft|abbr=on}} of sail<ref>{{cite web |title=''Charles W. Morgan'' \u2013 Whaling Ship |website=[[Mystic Seaport]] |url=http://www.mysticseaport.org/index.cfm?fuseaction=home.viewpage&page_id=B3E63C64-B3CA-45AE-A83D72C303A9C6BF |accessdate=28 February 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110515015019/http://www.mysticseaport.org/index.cfm?fuseaction=home.viewPage&page_id=B3E63C64-B3CA-45AE-A83D72C303A9C6BF |archivedate=15 May 2011}}</ref>\n| Ship notes=\n}}\n{{Infobox NRHP\n|embed=yes\n|name=''Charles W. Morgan''\n|nrhp_type = nhl\n|image =\n|caption =\n|location= [[Mystic, Connecticut]]\n|coordinates = {{coord|41|21|46.04|N|71|57|54.89|W|display=inline,title}}\n|locmapin = Connecticut#USA\n|map_width=300\n|built = 1841\n|architecture =\n|designated_nrhp_type= 13 November 1966<ref name=\"nhlsum\">{{cite web |url = http://tps.cr.nps.gov/nhl/detail.cfm?ResourceId=613&ResourceType=Structure |title = Charles W. Morgan (Bark) |accessdate = 2007-10-03 |work = National Historic Landmark summary listing |publisher = National Park Service |url-status = dead |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20100701125609/http://tps.cr.nps.gov/nhl/detail.cfm?ResourceId=613&ResourceType=Structure |archivedate = 2010-07-01}}</ref>\n|added = 13 November 1966<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|2007a|dateform=dmy}}</ref>\n|refnum = 66000804\n|nrhp_type2 = cp\n| nocat = yes\n|designated_nrhp_type2 = August 31, 1979\n|partof = [[Mystic Bridge Historic District]]\n|partof_refnum = 79002671\n}}\n|}\n\n'''''Charles W. Morgan''''' is an American whaling ship built in 1841 that was active during the 19th and early 20th centuries. Ships of this type were used to harvest the blubber of whales for whale oil which was commonly used in lamps. ''Charles W. Morgan'' has served as a museum ship since the 1940s and is now an exhibit at the [[Mystic Seaport]] museum in [[Mystic, Connecticut]]. She is the world's oldest surviving merchant vessel and the only surviving wooden whaling ship from the 19th century American merchant fleet.<ref name=\"nrhpinv\"/> She was designated a [[National Historic Landmark]] in 1966.\n\n== Construction ==\n''Charles W. Morgan'' (often referred to simply as \"the ''Morgan''\") was a whaling ship named for owner [[Charles Waln Morgan]] (1796\u20131861). He was a Philadelphian by birth; he moved to [[New Bedford, Massachusetts]] in 1818 and invested in several whalers over his career.<ref>{{cite web|title=Inventory of the Charles Waln Morgan Papers|publisher=New Bedford Whaling Museum|access-date=July 3, 2018|url=https://www.whalingmuseum.org/explore/library/finding-aids/mss41}}</ref> He chose Jethro and Zachariah Hillman's shipyard in New Bedford to construct a new ship,<ref name=Stackpole />{{rp|23}} and the ''Morgan''{{'s}} live oak keel was laid down in February 1841 and fastened together with copper bolts. The bow and stern pieces of live oak were secured to the keel by an apron piece. The sturdy stern post was strengthened with hemlock root and white oak. Yellow pine shipped from North Carolina was used for the ship's beams, and hemlock or [[hackmatack]] was used for the [[Knee (construction)|hanging knees]].<ref name=Stackpole />{{rp|29}}\n\nConstruction proceeded until April 19, 1841, when the workers went on strike, demanding a ten-hour work day.<ref name=Stackpole />{{rp|30}} The strike gathered support until it encompassed the shipyard, the oil refineries, and the cooper shops; Morgan was appointed chairman of the employers and given the task of resolving it.<ref name=Stackpole />{{rp|30}} He opposed their demands, and a meeting with four master mechanics ended in failure. An agreement was reached on May 6 when the workers accepted a 10\u00bd hour workday.<ref name=Stackpole />{{rp|32}} Work resumed on the ship without incident and she was launched on July 21, 1841.<ref name=Stackpole />{{rp|32}} ''Morgan'' was registered as {{convert|106+1/2|ft|m}} in length, {{convert|27|ft|2+1/2|in|m}} inches in [[beam (nautical)|breadth]], and {{convert|13|ft|7+1/4|in|m}} in depth.<ref name=Stackpole />{{rp|33}} Her displacement was 314 gross tons.<ref>{{Cite magazine |title=A Trip on the Whaling Ship Charles W. Morgan {{!}} History Under Sail |magazine=Yankee Magazine |url=http://www.yankeemagazine.com/article/new-england-101/charles-w-morgan |access-date=October 17, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe ''Morgan'' was outfitted at Rotch's Wharf for the next two months while preparations were made for her first voyage.<ref name=Stackpole />{{rp|34\u201335}} Captain Thomas Norton sailed her into the Atlantic alongside ''Adeline Gibbs'' and ''Nassau'' towards the [[Azores]].<ref name=Stackpole />{{rp|35}} A stop was made at Porto Pim (Horta) on [[Faial Island]] to gather supplies before crossing the Atlantic.  The ship passed Cape Horn, then charted a course to the north.<ref name=Stackpole />{{rp|38}} On December 13, the men launched in their whaleboats and took their first whale.<ref name=Stackpole />{{rp|43}} The ''Morgan'' entered the port of Callao in early February and departed again on the 10th for the [[Galapagos Islands]]. In 1844, the ship sailed to the Kodiak Grounds before sailing for home on August 18.<ref name=Stackpole />{{rp|60}} She returned to her home port in New Bedford on January 2, 1845.<ref name=Stackpole />{{rp|60}} The voyage of three years and three months resulted in 59 whales being processed for 1,600 barrels of sperm oil, 800 barrels of right whale oil, and five tons of whale bone.<ref name=Stackpole />{{rp|61}}\n\n== Service life ==\n[[File:Charles W Morgan 2008.jpg|thumb|left|250px]]\n\n''Charles W. Morgan'' made 37 voyages in her 80 years of service from her home port of New Bedford, Massachusetts, ranging in length from nine months to five years. She brought home a total of 54,483 barrels of sperm whale oil and 152,934 pounds of whalebone. She sailed in the Indian and South Atlantic Oceans, surviving ice and snow storms. Her crew survived a cannibal attack in the South Pacific. She was based in San Francisco between 1888 and 1904.\n\nThe ''Morgan'' had more than 1,000 whalemen of all races and nationalities in her lifetime. Her crew included sailors from Cape Verde, New Zealand, the [[Seychelles]], Guadeloupe, and [[Norfolk Island]].  The ship's crew averaged around 33 men per voyage. As with other whaleships in the 19th century, the ''Morgan'' was often home to the captain's family. She was owned and managed by the [[J. & W. R. Wing Company]] of New Bedford.<ref name=\"nyt1900\">{{cite news|title=Successful whaler returns|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=30 October 1900\n|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1900/10/30/102637026.pdf\n}}</ref>\n\nDuring her years of service, the ''Morgan'' was used in several movies, including ''[[Miss Petticoats]]'' (1916), ''[[Down to the Sea in Ships (1922 film)|Down to the Sea in Ships]]'' (1922), and ''[[Java Head (1923 film)|Java Head]]'' (1923).\n\n== Voyage summary ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Voyage !! Port !! Captain !! Departure !! Arrival !!  Mainly operated in\n|-\n| 1 || New Bedford || Thomas A. Norton || September 6, 1841 || January 2, 1845 || Pacific\n|-\n| 2 || New Bedford || J.D. Samson || June 10, 1845  ||  ||   Pacific\n|-\n| 3 || New Bedford || J.D. Samson  || June 5, 1849 ||  ||   Pacific\n|-\n| 4 || New Bedford || Tristram P. Ripley || September 20, 1853  ||  || North Pacific\n|-\n| 5 || New Bedford  || Thomas N. Fisher || September 15, 1856 ||  ||  North Pacific\n|-\n| 6 || New Bedford || James. A. Hamilton  || October 4, 1859 ||  ||  North Pacific\n|-\n| 7 || New Bedford || Thomas C. Landers || December 1, 1863 ||  ||  North Pacific\n|-\n| 8 || New Bedford || George Athearn   || July 17, 1867 ||  || Pacific\n|-\n| 9 || New Bedford || John M. Tinkham || September 26, 1871  ||  ||  Indian\n|-\n| 10 || New Bedford || John M. Tinkham || April 23, 1875 ||  || Atlantic\n|-\n| 11 || New Bedford || Thomas L. Ellis || July 17, 1878 ||  || Atlantic\n|-\n| 12 || New Bedford || Charles F. Keith || July 13, 1881 ||  || Pacific\n|-\n| 13 || New Bedford || George A. Smith || October 6, 1886 ||  ||  North Pacific\n|-\n| 14 || San Francisco || George A. Smith || December 4, 1887 ||  || North Pacific\n|-\n| 15 || San Francisco || John S. Layton || November 27, 1888 ||  || North Pacific\n|-\n| 16 || San Francisco || John S. Layton || December 5, 1889 ||  || Japan and Okhotsk\n|-\n| 17 || San Francisco || J. A. M. Earle || December 2, 1890 ||  || Japan and Okhotsk\n|-\n| 18 || San Francisco || J. A. M. Earle || November 24, 1891 ||  || Japan and Okhotsk\n|-\n| 19 || San Francisco || J. A. M. Earle  || December 8, 1892 ||  || Japan and Okhotsk\n|-\n| 20 || San Francisco || J. A. M. Earle || December 6, 1893 ||  ||  Japan and Okhotsk\n|-\n| 21 || San Francisco || J. A. M. Earle || December 2, 1895 ||  ||  Pacific\n|-\n| 22 || San Francisco || John S. Layton || December 3, 1896 ||  ||  Pacific\n|-\n| 23 || San Francisco || Thomas Scullion || November 11, 1897 ||  || Japan and Okhotsk\n|-\n| 24 || San Francisco  || Thomas Scullion || November 26, 1898 ||  || Japan and Okhotsk\n|-\n| 25 || San Francisco || Thomas Scullion || December 7, 1899 ||  ||  Japan and Okhotsk\n|-\n| 26 || San Francisco || J. A. M. Earle || November 22, 1900 ||  ||  Japan and Okhotsk\n|-\n| 27 || San Francisco || Thomas Scullion || November 27, 1901  ||  || Japan and Okhotsk\n|-\n| 28 || San Francisco || J. A. M. Earle || November 20, 1902 ||  || Japan and Okhotsk\n|-\n| 29 || San Francisco || J. A. M. Earle || November 18, 1903 ||  ||  Japan and Okhotsk\n|-\n| 30 || San Francisco || Edwin J. Reed || November 25, 1904 ||  ||  South Pacific\n|-\n| 31 || New Bedford || J. A. M. Earle, <br/> Hiram Nye || August 11, 1906 ||  ||  Atlantic\n|-\n| 32 || New Bedford || A. O. Gibbons, <br/> Charles S. Church || September 2, 1908 ||  || Atlantic\n|-\n| 33 || New Bedford || Charles S. Church || May 10, 1911 ||  || Atlantic\n|-\n| 34 || New Bedford || Benjamin D. Cleveland || September 7, 1916 ||  ||  Atlantic\n|-\n| 35 || Provincetown || Joseph F. Edwards || July 17, 1918 ||  || Atlantic\n|-\n| 36 || Provincetown || Joseph F. Edwards || October 18, 1919 ||  ||  Atlantic\n|-\n| 37 || Provincetown || N. Gonsalves || September 9, 1920 ||  ||  Atlantic\n|-\n| 38* || New Bedford || [[George Fred Tilton]] || May 7, 1925 || May 7, 1925  ||  \n|-\n| 39* || Fairhaven  || William H. Tripp || November 5, 1941 || November 8, 1941 || \n|-\n|}\n\n== Preservation ==\n''Charles W. Morgan'' was nearly destroyed in 1924 when the steamer ''Sankaty'' caught fire and broke free of her mooring lines.<ref name=Stackpole />{{rp|5}}<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=The Dukes County Intelligencer|volume=24|number=4|date=May 1983}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=Reminiscences of The Last Voyage of the Bark Wanderer|page=18|journal=[[American Neptune|The American Neptune]]|year=1949|publisher=Peabody Museum of Salem|url=https://books.google.com/?id=xzLSFspFuKAC&dq=Sankaty&q=Sankaty}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=Pacific Steam Navigation Company|journal=[[Sea Breezes (magazine)|Sea Breezes]]|volume=56|number=443|date=November 1982\n|url=https://books.google.com/?id=5qoPAAAAIAAJ&q=steamer+%2BSankaty&dq=steamer+%2BSankaty}}</ref> The burning ''Sankaty'' drifted across the river and into ''Morgan''{{'}}s port quarter, but the Fairhaven firemen managed to save her.<ref name=Stackpole />{{rp|5}} This event spurred Harry Neyland and some New Bedford citizens to restore and preserve the ''Morgan'',{{when|date=January 2018}} but the attempts were unsuccessful. Neyland then persuaded Colonel [[Edward Howland Robinson Green]] to save the ship.<ref name=Stackpole />{{rp|5}} Neyland appealed to Green that the ''Morgan'' was of historical importance and was a family heirloom because she was once co-owned by Green's grandfather and his wife's company.<ref name=Stackpole />{{rp|5}} Green had the ship towed to his estate in [[Round Hill (Dartmouth, Massachusetts)]]{{when|date=January 2018}} and founded Whaling Enshrined, consisting of himself, Neyland, and John Bullard, the great-grandson of [[Charles Morgan (businessman)|Charles Waln Morgan]].<ref name=Stackpole />{{rp|6}}\n\nThe ''Morgan'' underwent restoration by Captain [[George Fred Tilton]] and was turned into an exhibition for Green's estate in a berth constructed by Frank Taylor.<ref name=Stackpole />{{rp|6}} Green held a dedication ceremony on the 86th anniversary of the ship's launch and gave her to Whaling Enshrined on July 21, 1926.<ref name=Stackpole />{{rp|6}} The ship's fate came into question when Tilton died in 1932 and Green died in 1935, resulting in lengthy court proceedings over Green's estate.<ref name=Stackpole />{{rp|7\u20139}} The [[1938 New England hurricane]] damaged ''Morgan''{{'}}s hull and tore the sails; Whaling Enshrined attempted to secure funds for the ship but were unable to do so.<ref name=Stackpole />{{rp|9}}\n\nIn 1941, the ''Morgan'' was saved by the Marine Historical Association (later renamed [[Mystic Seaport]]) based on Taylor's word that the ship could be freed and towed to [[Mystic, Connecticut]].<ref name=Stackpole />{{rp|10}} Taylor's crew dug the ship from her berth and dredged a channel for her to pass through, but the first attempt to pull her free was unsuccessful. More digging and caulking of the ship preceded her successful tugging into the channel, and the century-old hull withstood the move and floated into bay with assistance from the Coast Guard cutter ''General Greene''.<ref name=Stackpole />{{rp|11}} She was towed to the old berth in Fairhaven for several days of preparations and repairs prior to the trip to Mystic.<ref name=Stackpole />{{rp|11}}\n\nOn November 5, 1941, ''General Greene'' pulled ''Charles W. Morgan'' from the wharf only to have her be caught by the tide and swept downstream, coming to rest on a mud flat and taking two hours to be freed.<ref name=Stackpole />{{rp|4}} The journey came to an end on November 8 when she passed through the Mystic bridge and was moored in the Mystic Seaport.<ref name=Stackpole />{{rp|17\u201318}} The Seaport took shape around ''Charles W. Morgan'' with the restoration of its buildings and historic ships that came to reside alongside the ''Morgan''.<ref name=Stackpole />{{rp|18}} \"Over it all, the ''Morgan'' presided like Old Neptune-the centerpiece, the king seated on a throne of gravel, towering high above the scene.\"<ref name=Stackpole />{{rp|19}}\n\n==Restoration==\n[[File:Charleswmorgan2010.jpg|thumb|right|200px|''Charles W. Morgan'' in dry-dock undergoing restoration]]\n\n''Charles W. Morgan'' arrived at Mystic Seaport in December 1941, and she was declared a National Historic Landmark and listed on the National Register of Historic Places in 1966.<ref name=\"nhlsum\"/><ref name=\"nrhpinv\">{{cite web|url={{NHLS url|id=66000804}}|format=pdf|title=The Charles W. Morgan|date=11 December 1974|first=Blanche Higgins|last=Schroer|first2=S. Sydney|last2=Bradford|work=National Register of Historic Places Inventory-Nomination|publisher=[[National Park Service]]}}and <br />{{cite web|url={{NHLS url|id=66000804|photos=y}}|format=pdf|title=Accompanying 4 photos, from 1974 and undated|work=National Register of Historic Places Inventory-Nomination|date=11 December 1974|publisher=[[National Park Service]]}}</ref> In 1971, [[Melbourne Brindle]] of [[Bridgeport, Connecticut]] designed four commemorative stamps of historic landmarks including the ''Morgan''.<ref name=\"brid\">{{cite web | url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/825046/the_bridgeport_post/? | title=Historic Stamps, Famed Car, Make October Special for Area Artist | publisher=The Bridgeport Post (Bridgeport, Connecticut) | date=3 October 1971 | accessdate=6 August 2014 | pages=31}}</ref>\n\nFor the first 30 years at Mystic Seaport, she was surrounded by a bed of sand to prevent her from sinking.  Even so, she was open to the public and was the centerpiece of a recreated 19th century maritime village museum inspired by [[Colonial Williamsburg]].  She is the only preserved 19th century whaling ship in the world.\n\nThe Mystic Seaport undertook a restoration and preservation project in 1968 to make her seaworthy, and the sand bed was removed.  Prior to the 1968 restoration, she had a wide white stripe painted on her sides with large black squares that resembled gun ports when viewed at a distance.  This \"camouflage\" was often employed by 19th century merchant ships to make them resemble warships so as to deter pirates and hostile navies.\n\nIn 2010, Mystic Seaport engaged in a multimillion-dollar project to restore the ship to seaworthy status. She was re-launched into the Mystic River on July 21, 2013, marking the 172nd anniversary of the vessel's initial launch.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/08/17/science/17ship.html?_r=1&hp|title=A Quest to Make the Morgan Seaworthy|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|department=Science|date=16 August 2010|last=Broad|first=William J.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mysticseaport.org/visit/explore/morgan|title=Charles W Morgan - Mystic Seaport|website=[[Mystic Seaport Museum]]|accessdate=2013-06-22}}</ref><ref name=nyt2013>{{cite news |last=Bond |first=Michaelle |title=Museum Relaunches Wooden Whaler Built in 1841 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/07/22/nyregion/museum-relaunches-wooden-whaler-built-in-1841.html |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |department=N.Y. / Region |date=21 July 2013}}</ref> During the summer of 2014, she sailed her 38th voyage on tour of New England seaports which included [[New London, Connecticut]], [[Newport, Rhode Island]], [[Boston]], and her home town of New Bedford, Massachusetts.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.theday.com/section/NWScwmorgan2014 |title=The 38th Voyage: Morgan readies to sail again |newspaper=[[The Day (New London)|The Day]] |date=May 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Ship CW Morgan.jpg|thumb|right|250px|1971 U.S. commemorative stamp honoring ''Charles W. Morgan'' by [[Melbourne Brindle]]]]\n\n==See also==\n{{Commons category|Charles W. Morgan (ship, 1841)|Charles W. Morgan}}\n{{Portal|Connecticut}}\n* [[List of National Historic Landmarks in Connecticut]]\n* [[National Register of Historic Places listings in New London County, Connecticut]]\n* [[List of museum ships]]\n\nOther preserved 19th-century sailing ships:\n* [[USS Constitution|USS ''Constitution'']]\n* [[USS Niagara (1813)|USS ''Niagara'']]\n* [[USS Constellation (1854)|USS ''Constellation'']]\n* ''[[Cutty Sark]]''\n* [[Effie M. Morrissey|''Effie M. Morrissey'' / ''Ernestina'']]\n* [[Coronet (yacht)|''Coronet'']]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n<ref name=Stackpole>{{cite book | title=The Charles W. Morgan | publisher=Meredith Press | author=Stackpole, Edouard | year=1967}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.glassian.org/Prism/Deck/Charles_W_Morgan ''Deck prisms on the Charles W. Morgan'']\n* {{WHD|AS0089|''Charles W. Morgan''}}\n\n{{Mystic Seaport |state=collapsed}}\n{{National Register of Historic Places}}\n{{Oldest surviving ships (pre-1919)}}\n\n[[Category:Whaling ships]]\n[[Category:Museum ships in Mystic, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Tall ships of the United States]]\n[[Category:Ships built in New Bedford, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:National Register of Historic Places in New London County, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Historic district contributing properties in Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Ships on the National Register of Historic Places in Connecticut]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the naval officer|Charles W. Morgan (naval officer)}}\n\n{{short description|American whaling ship built in 1841}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n|+''Charles W. Morgan''\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=Charles W Morgan.jpg\n|Ship caption=''Charles W. Morgan'' at [[Mystic Seaport]], [[Connecticut]]\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship country=United States\n|Ship flag={{shipboxflag|USA|1841}}\n|Ship name=\n|Ship owner=*[[Charles Waln Morgan]], 1841\u2013\n*[[J. & W. R. Wing Company]], c.1863{{spaced ndash}}c.1912<ref name=\"nrhpinv\" />\n*[[Edward Howland Robinson Green|Col. E H R Green]], c.1925\u20131941<ref name=\"nrhpinv\" />\n*Whaling Enshrined, Inc., 1941<ref name=\"nrhpinv\" />\n*[[Mystic Seaport]], 1941\u2013\n|Ship ordered=\n|Ship builder=Jethro and Zachariah Hillman, [[New Bedford, Massachusetts]]\n|Ship original cost=\n|Ship laid down=\n|Ship launched=1841\n|Ship acquired\n|Ship commissioned=\n|Ship decommissioned=\n|Ship in service=\n|Ship out of service=\n|Ship identification=*{{MMSI Number|367608930}}\n*Call sign: WDH3594\n|Ship renamed=\n|Ship fate=\n|Ship status=Museum ship\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n| Hide header=\n| Header caption=\n| Ship class=\n| Ship tonnage=351.3 [[Builder's Old Measurement#American tons burthen|(Old Tons)]]; 313.8 [[Gross Register Tonnage|(New Tons)]]<ref name = Davis>{{cite book |last=Davis |first=Lance E. |last2=Gallman |first2=Robert E. |last3=Gleiter |first3=Karen |date=1997 |url=https://www.nber.org/books/davi97-1 |title=In Pursuit of Leviathan: Technology, Institutions, Productivity, and Profits in American Whaling, 1816\u20131906 |chapter-url=https://www.nber.org/chapters/c8281.pdf |format=pdf |chapter=Chapter 6: Capital |at=Table 6.11 at p. 254 |location=Chicago |publisher=University of Chicago Press |isbn=0-226-13789-9}}  See [https://www.nber.org/chapters/c8281.pdf#page=3 p. 215] (pdf) & fn. 5 for discussion of the difference in tonnage measurements.</ref>\n| Ship length={{convert|113|ft|abbr=on}} LOA\n| Ship beam={{convert|27|ft|6|in|abbr=on}}\n| Ship draft=\n| Ship depth={{convert|17|ft|6|in|abbr=on}}\n| Ship sail plan=Double-topsail bark rig; {{convert|13000|sqft|abbr=on}} of sail<ref>{{cite web |title=''Charles W. Morgan'' \u2013 Whaling Ship |website=[[Mystic Seaport]] |url=http://www.mysticseaport.org/index.cfm?fuseaction=home.viewpage&page_id=B3E63C64-B3CA-45AE-A83D72C303A9C6BF |accessdate=28 February 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110515015019/http://www.mysticseaport.org/index.cfm?fuseaction=home.viewPage&page_id=B3E63C64-B3CA-45AE-A83D72C303A9C6BF |archivedate=15 May 2011}}</ref>\n| Ship notes=\n}}\n{{Infobox NRHP\n|embed=yes\n|name=''Charles W. Morgan''\n|nrhp_type = nhl\n|image =\n|caption =\n|location= [[Mystic, Connecticut]]\n|coordinates = {{coord|41|21|46.04|N|71|57|54.89|W|display=inline,title}}\n|locmapin = Connecticut#USA\n|map_width=300\n|built = 1841\n|architecture =\n|designated_nrhp_type= 13 November 1966<ref name=\"nhlsum\">{{cite web |url = http://tps.cr.nps.gov/nhl/detail.cfm?ResourceId=613&ResourceType=Structure |title = Charles W. Morgan (Bark) |accessdate = 2007-10-03 |work = National Historic Landmark summary listing |publisher = National Park Service |url-status = dead |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20100701125609/http://tps.cr.nps.gov/nhl/detail.cfm?ResourceId=613&ResourceType=Structure |archivedate = 2010-07-01}}</ref>\n|added = 13 November 1966<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|2007a|dateform=dmy}}</ref>\n|refnum = 66000804\n|nrhp_type2 = cp\n| nocat = yes\n|designated_nrhp_type2 = August 31, 1979\n|partof = [[Mystic Bridge Historic District]]\n|partof_refnum = 79002671\n}}\n|}\n\n'''''Charles W. Morgan''''' is an American whaling ship built in 1841 that was active during the 19th and early 20th centuries. Ships of this type were used to harvest the blubber of whales for whale oil which was commonly used in lamps. ''Charles W. Morgan'' has served as a museum ship since the 1940s and is now an exhibit at the [[Mystic Seaport]] museum in [[Mystic, Connecticut]]. She is the world's oldest surviving merchant vessel and the only surviving wooden whaling ship from the 19th century American merchant fleet.<ref name=\"nrhpinv\"/> She was designated a [[National Historic Landmark]] in 1966.\n\n== Construction ==\n''Charles W. Morgan'' (often referred to simply as \"the ''Morgan''\") was a whaling ship named for owner [[Charles Waln Morgan]] (1796\u20131861). He was a Philadelphian by birth; he moved to [[New Bedford, Massachusetts]] in 1818 and invested in several whalers over his career.<ref>{{cite web|title=Inventory of the Charles Waln Morgan Papers|publisher=New Bedford Whaling Museum|access-date=July 3, 2018|url=https://www.whalingmuseum.org/explore/library/finding-aids/mss41}}</ref> He chose Jethro and Zachariah Hillman's shipyard in New Bedford to construct a new ship,<ref name=Stackpole />{{rp|23}} and the ''Morgan''{{'s}} live oak keel was laid down in February 1841 and fastened together with copper bolts. The bow and stern pieces of live oak were secured to the keel by an apron piece. The sturdy stern post was strengthened with hemlock root and white oak. Yellow pine shipped from North Carolina was used for the ship's beams, and hemlock or [[hackmatack]] was used for the [[Knee (construction)|hanging knees]].<ref name=Stackpole />{{rp|29}}\n\nConstruction proceeded until April 19, 1841, when the workers went on strike, demanding a ten-hour work day.<ref name=Stackpole />{{rp|30}} The strike gathered support until it encompassed the shipyard, the oil refineries, and the cooper shops; Morgan was appointed chairman of the employers and given the task of resolving it.<ref name=Stackpole />{{rp|30}} He opposed their demands, and a meeting with four master mechanics ended in failure. An agreement was reached on May 6 when the workers accepted a 10\u00bd hour workday.<ref name=Stackpole />{{rp|32}} Work resumed on the ship without incident and she was launched on July 21, 1841.<ref name=Stackpole />{{rp|32}} ''Morgan'' was registered as {{convert|106+1/2|ft|m}} in length, {{convert|27|ft|2+1/2|in|m}} inches in [[beam (nautical)|breadth]], and {{convert|13|ft|7+1/4|in|m}} in depth.<ref name=Stackpole />{{rp|33}} Her displacement was 314 gross tons.<ref>{{Cite magazine |title=A Trip on the Whaling Ship Charles W. Morgan {{!}} History Under Sail |magazine=Yankee Magazine |url=http://www.yankeemagazine.com/article/new-england-101/charles-w-morgan |access-date=October 17, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe ''Morgan'' was outfitted at Rotch's Wharf for the next two months while preparations were made for her first voyage.<ref name=Stackpole />{{rp|34\u201335}} Captain Thomas Norton sailed her into the Atlantic alongside ''Adeline Gibbs'' and ''Nassau'' towards the [[Azores]].<ref name=Stackpole />{{rp|35}} A stop was made at Porto Pim (Horta) on [[Faial Island]] to gather supplies before crossing the Atlantic.  The ship passed Cape Horn, then charted a course to the north.<ref name=Stackpole />{{rp|38}} On December 13, the men launched in their whaleboats and took their first whale.<ref name=Stackpole />{{rp|43}} The ''Morgan'' entered the port of Callao in early February and departed again on the 10th for the [[Galapagos Islands]]. In 1844, the ship sailed to the Kodiak Grounds before sailing for home on August 18.<ref name=Stackpole />{{rp|60}} She returned to her home port in New Bedford on January 2, 1845.<ref name=Stackpole />{{rp|60}} The voyage of three years and three months resulted in 59 whales being processed for 1,600 barrels of sperm oil, 800 barrels of right whale oil, and five tons of whale bone.<ref name=Stackpole />{{rp|61}}\n\n== Service life ==\n[[File:Charles W Morgan 2008.jpg|thumb|left|250px]]\n\n''Charles W. Morgan'' made 37 voyages in her 80 years of service from her home port of New Bedford, Massachusetts, ranging in length from nine months to five years. She brought home a total of 54,483 barrels of sperm whale oil and 152,934 pounds of whalebone. She sailed in the Indian and South Atlantic Oceans, surviving ice and snow storms. Her crew survived a cannibal attack in the South Pacific. She was based in San Francisco between 1888 and 1904.\n\nThe ''Morgan'' had more than 1,000 whalemen of all races and nationalities in her lifetime. Her crew included sailors from Cape Verde, New Zealand, the [[Seychelles]], Guadeloupe, and [[Norfolk Island]].  The ship's crew averaged around 33 men per voyage. As with other whaleships in the 19th century, the ''Morgan'' was often home to the captain's family. She was owned and managed by the [[J. & W. R. Wing Company]] of New Bedford.<ref name=\"nyt1900\">{{cite news|title=Successful whaler returns|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=30 October 1900\n|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1900/10/30/102637026.pdf\n}}</ref>\n\nDuring her years of service, the ''Morgan'' was used in several movies, including ''[[Miss Petticoats]]'' (1916), ''[[Down to the Sea in Ships (1922 film)|Down to the Sea in Ships]]'' (1922), and ''[[Java Head (1923 film)|Java Head]]'' (1923).\n\n== Voyage summary ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Voyage !! Port !! Captain !! Departure !! Arrival !!  Mainly operated in\n|-\n| 1 || New Bedford || Thomas A. Norton || September 6, 1841 || January 2, 1845 || Pacific\n|-\n| 2 || New Bedford || J.D. Samson || June 10, 1845  ||  ||   Pacific\n|-\n| 3 || New Bedford || J.D. Samson  || June 5, 1849 ||  ||   Pacific\n|-\n| 4 || New Bedford || Tristram P. Ripley || September 20, 1853  ||  || North Pacific\n|-\n| 5 || New Bedford  || Thomas N. Fisher || September 15, 1856 ||  ||  North Pacific\n|-\n| 6 || New Bedford || James. A. Hamilton  || October 4, 1859 ||  ||  North Pacific\n|-\n| 7 || New Bedford || Thomas C. Landers || December 1, 1863 ||  ||  North Pacific\n|-\n| 8 || New Bedford || George Athearn   || July 17, 1867 ||  || Pacific\n|-\n| 9 || New Bedford || John M. Tinkham || September 26, 1871  ||  ||  Indian\n|-\n| 10 || New Bedford || John M. Tinkham || April 23, 1875 ||  || Atlantic\n|-\n| 11 || New Bedford || Thomas L. Ellis || July 17, 1878 ||  || Atlantic\n|-\n| 12 || New Bedford || Charles F. Keith || July 13, 1881 ||  || Pacific\n|-\n| 13 || New Bedford || George A. Smith || October 6, 1886 ||  ||  North Pacific\n|-\n| 14 || San Francisco || George A. Smith || December 4, 1887 ||  || North Pacific\n|-\n| 15 || San Francisco || John S. Layton || November 27, 1888 ||  || North Pacific\n|-\n| 16 || San Francisco || John S. Layton || December 5, 1889 ||  || Japan and Okhotsk\n|-\n| 17 || San Francisco || J. A. M. Earle || December 2, 1890 ||  || Japan and Okhotsk\n|-\n| 18 || San Francisco || J. A. M. Earle || November 24, 1891 ||  || Japan and Okhotsk\n|-\n| 19 || San Francisco || J. A. M. Earle  || December 8, 1892 ||  || Japan and Okhotsk\n|-\n| 20 || San Francisco || J. A. M. Earle || December 6, 1893 ||  ||  Japan and Okhotsk\n|-\n| 21 || San Francisco || J. A. M. Earle || December 2, 1895 ||  ||  Pacific\n|-\n| 22 || San Francisco || John S. Layton || December 3, 1896 ||  ||  Pacific\n|-\n| 23 || San Francisco || Thomas Scullion || November 11, 1897 ||  || Japan and Okhotsk\n|-\n| 24 || San Francisco  || Thomas Scullion || November 26, 1898 ||  || Japan and Okhotsk\n|-\n| 25 || San Francisco || Thomas Scullion || December 7, 1899 ||  ||  Japan and Okhotsk\n|-\n| 26 || San Francisco || J. A. M. Earle || November 22, 1900 ||  ||  Japan and Okhotsk\n|-\n| 27 || San Francisco || Thomas Scullion || November 27, 1901  ||  || Japan and Okhotsk\n|-\n| 28 || San Francisco || J. A. M. Earle || November 20, 1902 ||  || Japan and Okhotsk\n|-\n| 29 || San Francisco || J. A. M. Earle || November 18, 1903 ||  ||  Japan and Okhotsk\n|-\n| 30 || San Francisco || Edwin J. Reed || November 25, 1904 ||  ||  South Pacific\n|-\n| 31 || New Bedford || J. A. M. Earle, <br/> Hiram Nye || August 11, 1906 ||  ||  Atlantic\n|-\n| 32 || New Bedford || A. O. Gibbons, <br/> Charles S. Church || September 2, 1908 ||  || Atlantic\n|-\n| 33 || New Bedford || Charles S. Church || May 10, 1911 ||  || Atlantic\n|-\n| 34 || New Bedford || Benjamin D. Cleveland || September 7, 1916 ||  ||  Atlantic\n|-\n| 35 || Provincetown || Joseph F. Edwards || July 17, 1918 ||  || Atlantic\n|-\n| 36 || Provincetown || Joseph F. Edwards || October 18, 1919 ||  ||  Atlantic\n|-\n| 37 || Provincetown || N. Gonsalves || September 9, 1920 ||  ||  Atlantic\n|-\n| 38* || New Bedford || [[George Fred Tilton]] || May 7, 1925 || May 7, 1925  ||  \n|-\n| 39* || Fairhaven  || William H. Tripp || November 5, 1941 || November 8, 1941 || \n|-\n|}\n\n== Preservation ==\n''Charles W. Morgan'' was nearly destroyed in 1924 when the steamer ''Sankaty'' caught fire and broke free of her mooring lines.<ref name=Stackpole />{{rp|5}}<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=The Dukes County Intelligencer|volume=24|number=4|date=May 1983}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=Reminiscences of The Last Voyage of the Bark Wanderer|page=18|journal=[[American Neptune|The American Neptune]]|year=1949|publisher=Peabody Museum of Salem|url=https://books.google.com/?id=xzLSFspFuKAC&dq=Sankaty&q=Sankaty}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=Pacific Steam Navigation Company|journal=[[Sea Breezes (magazine)|Sea Breezes]]|volume=56|number=443|date=November 1982\n|url=https://books.google.com/?id=5qoPAAAAIAAJ&q=steamer+%2BSankaty&dq=steamer+%2BSankaty}}</ref> The burning ''Sankaty'' drifted across the river and into ''Morgan''{{'}}s port quarter, but the Fairhaven firemen managed to save her.<ref name=Stackpole />{{rp|5}} This event spurred Harry Neyland and some New Bedford citizens to restore and preserve the ''Morgan'',{{when|date=January 2018}} but the attempts were unsuccessful. Neyland then persuaded Colonel [[Edward Howland Robinson Green]] to save the ship.<ref name=Stackpole />{{rp|5}} Neyland appealed to Green that the ''Morgan'' was of historical importance and was a family heirloom because she was once co-owned by Green's grandfather and his wife's company.<ref name=Stackpole />{{rp|5}} Green had the ship towed to his estate in [[Round Hill (Dartmouth, Massachusetts)]]{{when|date=January 2018}} and founded Whaling Enshrined, consisting of himself, Neyland, and John Bullard, the great-grandson of [[Charles Morgan (businessman)|Charles Waln Morgan]].<ref name=Stackpole />{{rp|6}}\n\nThe ''Morgan'' underwent restoration by Captain [[George Fred Tilton]] and was turned into an exhibition for Green's estate in a berth constructed by Frank Taylor.<ref name=Stackpole />{{rp|6}} Green held a dedication ceremony on the 86th anniversary of the ship's launch and gave her to Whaling Enshrined on July 21, 1926.<ref name=Stackpole />{{rp|6}} The ship's fate came into question when Tilton died in 1932 and Green died in 1935, resulting in lengthy court proceedings over Green's estate.<ref name=Stackpole />{{rp|7\u20139}} The [[1938 New England hurricane]] damaged ''Morgan''{{'}}s hull and tore the sails; Whaling Enshrined attempted to secure funds for the ship but were unable to do so.<ref name=Stackpole />{{rp|9}}\n\nIn 1941, the ''Morgan'' was saved by the Marine Historical Association (later renamed [[Mystic Seaport]]) based on Taylor's word that the ship could be freed and towed to [[Mystic, Connecticut]].<ref name=Stackpole />{{rp|10}} Taylor's crew dug the ship from her berth and dredged a channel for her to pass through, but the first attempt to pull her free was unsuccessful. More digging and caulking of the ship preceded her successful tugging into the channel, and the century-old hull withstood the move and floated into bay with assistance from the Coast Guard cutter ''General Greene''.<ref name=Stackpole />{{rp|11}} She was towed to the old berth in Fairhaven for several days of preparations and repairs prior to the trip to Mystic.<ref name=Stackpole />{{rp|11}}\n\nOn November 5, 1941, ''General Greene'' pulled ''Charles W. Morgan'' from the wharf only to have her be caught by the tide and swept downstream, coming to rest on a mud flat and taking two hours to be freed.<ref name=Stackpole />{{rp|4}} The journey came to an end on November 8 when she passed through the Mystic bridge and was moored in the Mystic Seaport.<ref name=Stackpole />{{rp|17\u201318}} The Seaport took shape around ''Charles W. Morgan'' with the restoration of its buildings and historic ships that came to reside alongside the ''Morgan''.<ref name=Stackpole />{{rp|18}} \"Over it all, the ''Morgan'' presided like Old Neptune-the centerpiece, the king seated on a throne of gravel, towering high above the scene.\"<ref name=Stackpole />{{rp|19}}\n\n==Restoration==\n[[File:Charleswmorgan2010.jpg|thumb|right|200px|''Charles W. Morgan'' in dry-dock undergoing restoration]]\n\n''Charles W. Morgan'' arrived at Mystic Seaport in December 1941, and she was declared a National Historic Landmark and listed on the National Register of Historic Places in 1966.<ref name=\"nhlsum\"/><ref name=\"nrhpinv\">{{cite web|url={{NHLS url|id=66000804}}|format=pdf|title=The Charles W. Morgan|date=11 December 1974|first=Blanche Higgins|last=Schroer|first2=S. Sydney|last2=Bradford|work=National Register of Historic Places Inventory-Nomination|publisher=[[National Park Service]]}}and <br />{{cite web|url={{NHLS url|id=66000804|photos=y}}|format=pdf|title=Accompanying 4 photos, from 1974 and undated|work=National Register of Historic Places Inventory-Nomination|date=11 December 1974|publisher=[[National Park Service]]}}</ref> In 1971, [[Melbourne Brindle]] of [[Bridgeport, Connecticut]] designed four commemorative stamps of historic landmarks including the ''Morgan''.<ref name=\"brid\">{{cite web | url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/825046/the_bridgeport_post/? | title=Historic Stamps, Famed Car, Make October Special for Area Artist | publisher=The Bridgeport Post (Bridgeport, Connecticut) | date=3 October 1971 | accessdate=6 August 2014 | pages=31}}</ref>\n\nFor the first 30 years at Mystic Seaport, she was surrounded by a bed of sand to prevent her from sinking.  Even so, she was open to the public and was the centerpiece of a recreated 19th century maritime village museum inspired by [[Colonial Williamsburg]].  She is the only preserved 19th century whaling ship in the world.\n\nThe Mystic Seaport undertook a restoration and preservation project in 1968 to make her seaworthy, and the sand bed was removed.  Prior to the 1968 restoration, she had a wide white stripe painted on her sides with large black squares that resembled gun ports when viewed at a distance.  This \"camouflage\" was often employed by 19th century merchant ships to make them resemble warships so as to deter pirates and hostile navies.\n\nIn 2010, Mystic Seaport engaged in a multimillion-dollar project to restore the ship to seaworthy status. She was re-launched into the Mystic River on July 21, 2013, marking the 172nd anniversary of the vessel's initial launch.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/08/17/science/17ship.html?_r=1&hp|title=A Quest to Make the Morgan Seaworthy|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|department=Science|date=16 August 2010|last=Broad|first=William J.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mysticseaport.org/visit/explore/morgan|title=Charles W Morgan - Mystic Seaport|website=[[Mystic Seaport Museum]]|accessdate=2013-06-22}}</ref><ref name=nyt2013>{{cite news |last=Bond |first=Michaelle |title=Museum Relaunches Wooden Whaler Built in 1841 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/07/22/nyregion/museum-relaunches-wooden-whaler-built-in-1841.html |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |department=N.Y. / Region |date=21 July 2013}}</ref> During the summer of 2014, she sailed her 38th voyage on tour of New England seaports which included [[New London, Connecticut]], [[Newport, Rhode Island]], [[Boston]], and her home town of New Bedford, Massachusetts.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.theday.com/section/NWScwmorgan2014 |title=The 38th Voyage: Morgan readies to sail again |newspaper=[[The Day (New London)|The Day]] |date=May 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Ship CW Morgan.jpg|thumb|right|250px|1971 U.S. commemorative stamp honoring ''Charles W. Morgan'' by [[Melbourne Brindle]]]]\n\n==See also==\n{{Commons category|Charles W. Morgan (ship, 1841)|Charles W. Morgan}}\n{{Portal|Connecticut}}\n* [[List of National Historic Landmarks in Connecticut]]\n* [[National Register of Historic Places listings in New London County, Connecticut]]\n* [[List of museum ships]]\n\nOther preserved 19th-century sailing ships:\n* [[USS Constitution|USS ''Constitution'']]\n* [[USS Niagara (1813)|USS ''Niagara'']]\n* [[USS Constellation (1854)|USS ''Constellation'']]\n* ''[[Cutty Sark]]''\n* [[Effie M. Morrissey|''Effie M. Morrissey'' / ''Ernestina'']]\n* [[Coronet (yacht)|''Coronet'']]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n<ref name=Stackpole>{{cite book | title=The Charles W. Morgan | publisher=Meredith Press | author=Stackpole, Edouard | year=1967}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.glassian.org/Prism/Deck/Charles_W_Morgan ''Deck prisms on the Charles W. Morgan'']\n* {{WHD|AS0089|''Charles W. Morgan''}}\n\n{{Mystic Seaport |state=collapsed}}\n{{National Register of Historic Places}}\n{{Oldest surviving ships (pre-1919)}}\n\n[[Category:Whaling ships]]\n[[Category:Museum ships in Mystic, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Tall ships of the United States]]\n[[Category:Ships built in New Bedford, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:National Register of Historic Places in New London County, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Historic district contributing properties in Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Ships on the National Register of Historic Places in Connecticut]]\n", "name_user": "SpaceNavy", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added ship class", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charles_W._Morgan_(ship)"}
{"title_page": "Samuel Wesley Stratton", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| name          = Samuel W. Stratton\n| image         = Samuel Wesley Stratton, 1905.jpg\n| caption       = Samuel Wesley Stratton, 1905\n| order         = 8th\n| title         = [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology|President of the Massachusetts Institute of Technology]]\n| term_start    = {{start date|1923|01|01}}\n| term_end      = {{end date|1930|01|30}}\n| predecessor   = [[Elihu Thomson]] {{small|(acting)}}\n| successor     = [[Karl Taylor Compton]]\n| order1        = 1st\n| title1        = Director of the [[National Bureau of Standards]]\n| term_start1   = {{start date|1901|03|11}}\n| term_end1     = {{end date|1922|12|31}}\n| president1    = {{ublist|[[William McKinley]]|[[Theodore Roosevelt]]|[[William Howard Taft]]|[[Woodrow Wilson]]|[[Warren G. Harding]]}}\n| predecessor1  = \n| successor1    = [[George K. Burgess]]\n| birth_date    = {{birth date|1861|7|18}}\n| birth_place   = [[Litchfield, Illinois|Litchfield]], [[Illinois]]\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|1931|10|18|1861|7|18}}\n| death_place   = [[Boston]], [[Massachusetts]]\n| resting_place = Mountain View Cemetery, [[Altadena, California]]\n| alma_mater    = [[University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign|Illinois Industrial University at Urbana]]\n| module        = \n  {{Infobox academic | child=yes\n  | discipline        = Physics\n  | workplaces        = {{ublist|[[University of Chicago]]}}\n  | academic_advisors = \n  | doctoral_students = \n  | notable_students  = \n  | known_for         = \n  | influences        = \n  | influenced        = \n  | awards            = {{ublist|[[Elliott Cresson Medal]] (1912)|[[Public Welfare Medal]] (1917)}}\n  }}\n}}\n\n'''Samuel Wesley Stratton''' (July 18, 1861 \u2013 October 18, 1931) was an administrator in the American government, physicist, and educator.\n\n== Life and work ==\nStratton was born on farm in [[Litchfield, Illinois]] on July 18, 1861. In his youth he kept farm machinery in repair and worked as a mechanic and carpenter. He worked his way through [[University of Illinois at Urbana\u2013Champaign|Illinois Industrial University at Urbana]] (later the University of Illinois), receiving his bachelor of science degree in mechanical engineering in 1884. He became an instructor in mathematics and physics following his graduation, and in 1889, when Physics department head Theodore B. Comstock, Professor of Mining Engineering and Physics, inexplicably failed to return to campus after the summer vacation, Stratton was appointed head<ref name=\"CenturyofPhysics\">{{cite paper |url=https://www.ideals.illinois.edu/handle/2142/48722 |title=A Century of Physics at the University of Illinois: A talk given before the History of Science Society in December 1967 |first=Gerald Marks |last=Almy |date=December 1967 |access-date=June 5, 2017 |work=University of Illinois}}</ref> of the Department of Physics by regent [[Selim Peabody|Selim Hobart Peabody]]. As Physics head, Stratton organized a formal curriculum in electrical engineering, which was taught in the Physics Department until a separate department of electrical engineering was established in 1898.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://www.ideals.illinois.edu/handle/2142/14488 |title=A History of the College of Engineering of the University of Illinois 1868-1945. Part I |last1=Baker |first1=Ira Osborn |last2=King |first2=Everett E. |location=Urbana, Illinois |publisher=University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign |year=1947 |access-date=June 5, 2017}}</ref> Stratton moved to the [[University of Chicago]] in 1892 as Assistant Professor of Physics, then Associate Professor in 1895 and Professor in 1898.\n\nStratton served in the [[Illinois Naval Militia]] from 1895, as a lieutenant in the Navy in the [[Spanish\u2013American War]], and from 1904 to 1912 served as commander in charge of the [[Naval militia|Naval Militia]] in the [[Washington, D.C.|District of Columbia]].\n[[File:Director Stratton in the Evening Star, 1901.jpg|thumb|left|Dr. Stratton in the Evening Star, 1901]]\nIn 1899 he was asked to head the [[U.S. National Geodetic Survey|U.S. Coast and Geodetic Survey's]] Office of Weights and Measures, where he developed the plan for the establishment of a bureau of standards. He won the support for his plans from Secretary of the Treasury [[Lyman J. Gage]] and in March 1901, President [[William McKinley]] appointed him the first director of the [[National Institute of Standards and Technology|National Bureau of Standards]]. He served until 1923. Under his leadership it grew from 24 to 900 employees scattered over 14 buildings. His operation was designed to recruit recent college graduates, train them, and feed them into private industry and its higher salaries. His team was called \"lowest-paid corps of first-rank scientists ever assembled by any government.\"<ref name=\"time.com\">{{cite news |magazine=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,715909,00.html |title=Science: Stratton and Edison |date=July 25, 1923 |access-date=December 25, 2009 |url-access=subscription}}</ref> The Bureau worked hand in glove with industry to undertake research that the private sector required but could not finance itself.\n\nHe was awarded the [[Elliott Cresson Medal]] of [[The Franklin Institute]] in 1912. In 1917 Stratton was awarded the [[Public Welfare Medal]] from the [[United States National Academy of Sciences|National Academy of Sciences]].<ref name=PublicWelfare>{{cite web |title=Public Welfare Award |url=http://www.nasonline.org/site/PageServer?pagename=AWARDS_pwm |publisher=[[National Academy of Sciences]] |accessdate=February 14, 2011}}</ref>\n\nHis boss, then Secretary of Commerce (later President) [[Herbert Hoover]] had used the occasion of Stratton's departure from government service as an opportunity to bemoan the low salaries paid to government scientists.<ref name=\"query.nytimes.com\">{{cite news |newspaper=[[New York Times]] |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=9F0DE3DA1E3EEE3ABC4A52DFB6678389639EDE |title=Elect Dr. Stratton President of M.I.T. |date=October 12, 1922 |accessdate=December 20, 2009 |url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n[[File:Samuel Wesley Stratton, 1922.jpg|thumb|Samuel Wesley Stratton, 1920s]]\nIn January 1923 he became the eighth president of [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology|M.I.T.]] and served for seven years. In his inaugural address he said: \"The terms pure and applied science have not the same distinction as formerly. The same men, methods and equipment are involved in getting at the facts, whether they are needed in solving problems in industry or in extending our knowledge of principals. There are few cases of the latter that do not find immediate application.\" Tying education to industry, he said that industry that had once been slow to seize upon scientific advances was now demanding them.<ref>{{cite news |newspaper=[[New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1923/06/12/archives/mit-inaugurates-stratton-as-head-new-executive-in-address-stresses.html |title=M.I.T. Inaugurates Stratton as Head |date=June 12, 1923 |accessdate=December 19, 2009 |url-access=subscription}}</ref> As recounted by ''Time'' magazine, \"he demonstrated the economic wisdom of generous support for research in pure science. He said that the automotive industry must find a substitute for gasoline, on which the elder Edison commented that the electric storage battery has already filled the bill. Edison looks for all transportation and industry to be electrified.\"<ref name=\"time.com\" />\n\nIn 1927, he served as one of three members as an Advisory Committee to Massachusetts Governor [[Alvan T. Fuller]], along with President [[Abbott Lawrence Lowell]] of Harvard and Probate Judge [[Robert Grant (novelist)|Robert Grant]]. They were tasked with reviewing the trial of [[Sacco and Vanzetti]] to determine whether the trial had been fair.<ref>{{cite news |newspaper=[[New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1927/06/02/archives/appoints-advisers-for-sacco-inquiry-fuller-picks-exjudge-grant.html |title=Appoints Advisers for Sacco Inquiry |date=June 2, 1927 |accessdate=January 6, 2010 |url-access=subscription}}</ref> Stratton, the one member who was not a [[Boston Brahmin]], maintained the lowest public profile of the three committee members and hardly spoke during its hearings.<ref>{{cite book |first=Bruce |last=Watson |title=Sacco and Vanzetti: The Men, the Murders, and the Judgment of Mankind |location=New York |publisher=Viking |year=2007 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/saccovanzettimen00wats/page/311 311\u20133] |isbn=978-0670063536 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/saccovanzettimen00wats/page/311 }}</ref>\n\nUpon his retirement in 1930 he became the first chairman of the MIT Corporation under a new plan of organization that he had devised. A lifelong bachelor, Stratton belonged to numerous private clubs. The carpentry he learned in his youth remained a lifelong hobby.\n\nFrance made him a Chevalier of the [[L\u00e9gion d'honneur|Legion of Honor]] in 1909, and he received honorary degrees from the [[University of Cambridge]] and [[Yale University]] among others.<ref name=\"query.nytimes.com\"/>\n\nOn October 18, 1931, he died of heart disease at his home in [[Back Bay, Boston|Boston's Back Bay]] while dictating a tribute to his friend [[Thomas Edison]], who died earlier in the day.<ref>{{cite news |newspaper=[[New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1931/10/19/archives/dr-sw-stratton-educator-is-dead-former-president-of-mit-succumbs.html |title=Dr. S.W. Stratton, Educator, is Dead |date=October 19, 1931 |access-date=December 18, 2009 |url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nHe is buried at Mountain View Cemetery and Mausoleum in [[Altadena, California]].<ref>{{cite web |work=[[Find a Grave]] |url=https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/20010 |title=Samuel Wesley Stratton |access-date=December 21, 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"lat-1931oct25\">{{cite news |url=https://latimes.newspapers.com/image/380605662/ |title=Obituary: Stratton |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=October 25, 1931 |page=22 |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |url-access=subscription |quote=Private funeral services for Dr. Samuel Wesley Stratton. who passed away October 18 in Boston, Mass., will be held at 1 p.m. Monday at the grave in Mountain View Cemetery, Pasadena.}} [https://search.proquest.com/docview/162497032/ Alternate Link] via [[ProQuest]].</ref>\n\nThe [[United States Department of Commerce|Commerce Department's]] [[National Institute of Standards and Technology]], formerly the National Bureau of Standards, has presented the Samuel Wesley Stratton Award annually since 1962 for outstanding scientific or engineering achievements in support of the objectives of the National Institute of Standards and Technology.\n\nNote that the [[Campus of the Massachusetts Institute of Technology#Stratton Student Center (1968)|Stratton Student Center]] on the MIT campus is dedicated to a different former president of MIT, [[Julius Adams Stratton]].\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Sources==\n* ''New York Times'': [https://www.nytimes.com/1931/10/19/archives/dr-sw-stratton-educator-is-dead-former-president-of-mit-succumbs.html \"Dr. S.W. stratton, Educaor, is Dead,\" October 19, 1931], accessed Dec 18, 2009\n* MIT: [http://libraries.mit.edu/archives/mithistory/biographies/s-stratton.html \"SAMUEL WESLEY STRATTON, 1861-1931\"], accessed Dec 21, 2009\n* MIT: [http://libraries.mit.edu/archives/exhibits/inaugurations/s-stratton.html \"Stratton: Inaugural Address], accessed Dec. 22, 2009\n\n<!--\nPublications\nbooks.nap.edu/html/biomems/sstratton.pdf\n-->\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikisource author}}\n{{commonscat-inline}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-gov}}\n{{s-new|office}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Director of the [[National Bureau of Standards]]|years=1901 \u2013 1922}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[George K. Burgess]]}}\n{{s-break}}\n{{s-aca}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Ernest Fox Nichols]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=President of the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]]|years=1923 \u2013 1930}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Karl Taylor Compton]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{MIT presidents}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stratton, Samuel Wesley}}\n[[Category:1861 births]]\n[[Category:1931 deaths]]\n[[Category:University of Chicago faculty]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the Massachusetts Institute of Technology]]\n[[Category:Recipients of awards from the United States National Academy of Sciences]]\n[[Category:University of Illinois at Urbana\u2013Champaign alumni]]\n[[Category:NIST Directors]]\n[[Category:People from Litchfield, Illinois]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| name          = Samuel W. Stratton\n| image         = Samuel Wesley Stratton, 1905.jpg\n| caption       = Samuel Wesley Stratton, 1905\n| order         = 8th\n| title         = [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology|President of the Massachusetts Institute of Technology]]\n| term_start    = {{start date|1923|01|01}}\n| term_end      = {{end date|1930|01|30}}\n| predecessor   = [[Elihu Thomson]] {{small|(acting)}}\n| successor     = [[Karl Taylor Compton]]\n| order1        = 1st\n| title1        = Director of the [[National Bureau of Standards]]\n| term_start1   = {{start date|1901|03|11}}\n| term_end1     = {{end date|1922|12|31}}\n| president1    = {{ublist|[[William McKinley]]|[[Theodore Roosevelt]]|[[William Howard Taft]]|[[Woodrow Wilson]]|[[Warren G. Harding]]}}\n| predecessor1  = \n| successor1    = [[George K. Burgess]]\n| birth_date    = {{birth date|1861|7|18}}\n| birth_place   = [[Litchfield, Illinois|Litchfield]], [[Illinois]]\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|1931|10|18|1861|7|18}}\n| death_place   = [[Boston]], [[Massachusetts]]\n| resting_place = Mountain View Cemetery, [[Altadena, California]]\n| alma_mater    = [[University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign|Illinois Industrial University at Urbana]]\n| module        = \n  {{Infobox academic | child=yes\n  | discipline        = Physics\n  | workplaces        = {{ublist|[[University of Chicago]]}}\n  | academic_advisors = \n  | doctoral_students = \n  | notable_students  = \n  | known_for         = \n  | influences        = \n  | influenced        = \n  | awards            = {{ublist|[[Elliott Cresson Medal]] (1912)|[[Public Welfare Medal]] (1917)}}\n  }}\n}}\n\n'''Samuel Wesley Stratton''' (July 18, 1861 \u2013 October 18, 1931) was an administrator in the American government, physicist, and educator.\n\n== Life and work ==\nStratton was born on farm in [[Litchfield, Illinois]] on July 18, 1861. In his youth he kept farm machinery in repair and worked as a mechanic and carpenter. He worked his way through [[University of Illinois at Urbana\u2013Champaign|Illinois Industrial University at Urbana]] (later the University of Illinois), receiving his bachelor of science degree in mechanical engineering in 1884. He became an instructor in mathematics and physics following his graduation, and in 1889, when Physics department head Theodore B. Comstock, Professor of Mining Engineering and Physics, inexplicably failed to return to campus after the summer vacation, Stratton was appointed head<ref name=\"CenturyofPhysics\">{{cite paper |url=https://www.ideals.illinois.edu/handle/2142/48722 |title=A Century of Physics at the University of Illinois: A talk given before the History of Science Society in December 1967 |first=Gerald Marks |last=Almy |date=December 1967 |access-date=June 5, 2017 |work=University of Illinois}}</ref> of the Department of Physics by regent [[Selim Peabody|Selim Hobart Peabody]]. As Physics head, Stratton organized a formal curriculum in electrical engineering, which was taught in the Physics Department until a separate department of electrical engineering was established in 1898.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://www.ideals.illinois.edu/handle/2142/14488 |title=A History of the College of Engineering of the University of Illinois 1868-1945. Part I |last1=Baker |first1=Ira Osborn |last2=King |first2=Everett E. |location=Urbana, Illlinois |publisher=University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign |year=1947 |access-date=June 5, 2017}}</ref> Stratton moved to the [[University of Chicago]] in 1892 as Assistant Professor of Physics, then Associate Professor in 1895 and Professor in 1898.\n\nStratton served in the [[Illinois Naval Militia]] from 1895, as a lieutenant in the Navy in the [[Spanish\u2013American War]], and from 1904 to 1912 served as commander in charge of the [[Naval militia|Naval Militia]] in the [[Washington, D.C.|District of Columbia]].\n[[File:Director Stratton in the Evening Star, 1901.jpg|thumb|left|Dr. Stratton in the Evening Star, 1901]]\nIn 1899 he was asked to head the [[U.S. National Geodetic Survey|U.S. Coast and Geodetic Survey's]] Office of Weights and Measures, where he developed the plan for the establishment of a bureau of standards. He won the support for his plans from Secretary of the Treasury [[Lyman J. Gage]] and in March 1901, President [[William McKinley]] appointed him the first director of the [[National Institute of Standards and Technology|National Bureau of Standards]]. He served until 1923. Under his leadership it grew from 24 to 900 employees scattered over 14 buildings. His operation was designed to recruit recent college graduates, train them, and feed them into private industry and its higher salaries. His team was called \"lowest-paid corps of first-rank scientists ever assembled by any government.\"<ref name=\"time.com\">{{cite news |magazine=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,715909,00.html |title=Science: Stratton and Edison |date=July 25, 1923 |access-date=December 25, 2009 |url-access=subscription}}</ref> The Bureau worked hand in glove with industry to undertake research that the private sector required but could not finance itself.\n\nHe was awarded the [[Elliott Cresson Medal]] of [[The Franklin Institute]] in 1912. In 1917 Stratton was awarded the [[Public Welfare Medal]] from the [[United States National Academy of Sciences|National Academy of Sciences]].<ref name=PublicWelfare>{{cite web |title=Public Welfare Award |url=http://www.nasonline.org/site/PageServer?pagename=AWARDS_pwm |publisher=[[National Academy of Sciences]] |accessdate=February 14, 2011}}</ref>\n\nHis boss, then Secretary of Commerce (later President) [[Herbert Hoover]] had used the occasion of Stratton's departure from government service as an opportunity to bemoan the low salaries paid to government scientists.<ref name=\"query.nytimes.com\">{{cite news |newspaper=[[New York Times]] |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=9F0DE3DA1E3EEE3ABC4A52DFB6678389639EDE |title=Elect Dr. Stratton President of M.I.T. |date=October 12, 1922 |accessdate=December 20, 2009 |url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n[[File:Samuel Wesley Stratton, 1922.jpg|thumb|Samuel Wesley Stratton, 1920s]]\nIn January 1923 he became the eighth president of [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology|M.I.T.]] and served for seven years. In his inaugural address he said: \"The terms pure and applied science have not the same distinction as formerly. The same men, methods and equipment are involved in getting at the facts, whether they are needed in solving problems in industry or in extending our knowledge of principals. There are few cases of the latter that do not find immediate application.\" Tying education to industry, he said that industry that had once been slow to seize upon scientific advances was now demanding them.<ref>{{cite news |newspaper=[[New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1923/06/12/archives/mit-inaugurates-stratton-as-head-new-executive-in-address-stresses.html |title=M.I.T. Inaugurates Stratton as Head |date=June 12, 1923 |accessdate=December 19, 2009 |url-access=subscription}}</ref> As recounted by ''Time'' magazine, \"he demonstrated the economic wisdom of generous support for research in pure science. He said that the automotive industry must find a substitute for gasoline, on which the elder Edison commented that the electric storage battery has already filled the bill. Edison looks for all transportation and industry to be electrified.\"<ref name=\"time.com\" />\n\nIn 1927, he served as one of three members as an Advisory Committee to Massachusetts Governor [[Alvan T. Fuller]], along with President [[Abbott Lawrence Lowell]] of Harvard and Probate Judge [[Robert Grant (novelist)|Robert Grant]]. They were tasked with reviewing the trial of [[Sacco and Vanzetti]] to determine whether the trial had been fair.<ref>{{cite news |newspaper=[[New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1927/06/02/archives/appoints-advisers-for-sacco-inquiry-fuller-picks-exjudge-grant.html |title=Appoints Advisers for Sacco Inquiry |date=June 2, 1927 |accessdate=January 6, 2010 |url-access=subscription}}</ref> Stratton, the one member who was not a [[Boston Brahmin]], maintained the lowest public profile of the three committee members and hardly spoke during its hearings.<ref>{{cite book |first=Bruce |last=Watson |title=Sacco and Vanzetti: The Men, the Murders, and the Judgment of Mankind |location=New York |publisher=Viking |year=2007 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/saccovanzettimen00wats/page/311 311\u20133] |isbn=978-0670063536 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/saccovanzettimen00wats/page/311 }}</ref>\n\nUpon his retirement in 1930 he became the first chairman of the MIT Corporation under a new plan of organization that he had devised. A lifelong bachelor, Stratton belonged to numerous private clubs. The carpentry he learned in his youth remained a lifelong hobby.\n\nFrance made him a Chevalier of the [[L\u00e9gion d'honneur|Legion of Honor]] in 1909, and he received honorary degrees from the [[University of Cambridge]] and [[Yale University]] among others.<ref name=\"query.nytimes.com\"/>\n\nOn October 18, 1931, he died of heart disease at his home in [[Back Bay, Boston|Boston's Back Bay]] while dictating a tribute to his friend [[Thomas Edison]], who died earlier in the day.<ref>{{cite news |newspaper=[[New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1931/10/19/archives/dr-sw-stratton-educator-is-dead-former-president-of-mit-succumbs.html |title=Dr. S.W. Stratton, Educator, is Dead |date=October 19, 1931 |access-date=December 18, 2009 |url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nHe is buried at Mountain View Cemetery and Mausoleum in [[Altadena, California]].<ref>{{cite web |work=[[Find a Grave]] |url=https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/20010 |title=Samuel Wesley Stratton |access-date=December 21, 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"lat-1931oct25\">{{cite news |url=https://latimes.newspapers.com/image/380605662/ |title=Obituary: Stratton |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=October 25, 1931 |page=22 |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |url-access=subscription |quote=Private funeral services for Dr. Samuel Wesley Stratton. who passed away October 18 in Boston, Mass., will be held at 1 p.m. Monday at the grave in Mountain View Cemetery, Pasadena.}} [https://search.proquest.com/docview/162497032/ Alternate Link] via [[ProQuest]].</ref>\n\nThe [[United States Department of Commerce|Commerce Department's]] [[National Institute of Standards and Technology]], formerly the National Bureau of Standards, has presented the Samuel Wesley Stratton Award annually since 1962 for outstanding scientific or engineering achievements in support of the objectives of the National Institute of Standards and Technology.\n\nNote that the [[Campus of the Massachusetts Institute of Technology#Stratton Student Center (1968)|Stratton Student Center]] on the MIT campus is dedicated to a different former president of MIT, [[Julius Adams Stratton]].\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Sources==\n* ''New York Times'': [https://www.nytimes.com/1931/10/19/archives/dr-sw-stratton-educator-is-dead-former-president-of-mit-succumbs.html \"Dr. S.W. stratton, Educaor, is Dead,\" October 19, 1931], accessed Dec 18, 2009\n* MIT: [http://libraries.mit.edu/archives/mithistory/biographies/s-stratton.html \"SAMUEL WESLEY STRATTON, 1861-1931\"], accessed Dec 21, 2009\n* MIT: [http://libraries.mit.edu/archives/exhibits/inaugurations/s-stratton.html \"Stratton: Inaugural Address], accessed Dec. 22, 2009\n\n<!--\nPublications\nbooks.nap.edu/html/biomems/sstratton.pdf\n-->\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikisource author}}\n{{commonscat-inline}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-gov}}\n{{s-new|office}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Director of the [[National Bureau of Standards]]|years=1901 \u2013 1922}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[George K. Burgess]]}}\n{{s-break}}\n{{s-aca}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Ernest Fox Nichols]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=President of the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]]|years=1923 \u2013 1930}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Karl Taylor Compton]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{MIT presidents}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stratton, Samuel Wesley}}\n[[Category:1861 births]]\n[[Category:1931 deaths]]\n[[Category:University of Chicago faculty]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the Massachusetts Institute of Technology]]\n[[Category:Recipients of awards from the United States National Academy of Sciences]]\n[[Category:University of Illinois at Urbana\u2013Champaign alumni]]\n[[Category:NIST Directors]]\n[[Category:People from Litchfield, Illinois]]\n", "name_user": "BuffaloBob", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLife and work:correctd spelling", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Samuel_Wesley_Stratton"}
{"title_page": "My Immortal (fan fiction)", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{Tone|date=April 2020}}\n{{POV|date=April 2020}}\n}}\n{{Infobox book\n| name          = My Immortal [[Columbine High School Massacre]]\n| title_orig    = \n| translator    = [[Adolf Hitler]]\n| image         = \n| caption = \n| author        = \"XXXbloodyrists666XXX\" (Cedric the Entertainer)\n| country       = [[The Principality of Sealand]]\n| language      = [[Ebola]]\n| series        = ''[[Harry Potter]]'' {{small|(non-canonical fan fiction)}}\n| genre         = [|Fantasy]] of a wikipedia mod getting the big boy cummies, [[drama]], [[neonatal]] [[child pornography]] [[sandpaper]]\n| publisher     = [[Large Hadron Collider]] - [[Taliban]] - [[Russian Mafia]]\n| release_date  = 2006\u20132007 - Berlin wall baby uuuuhhhhh let me nut pleassssee oh my i would love [[Nicholas Cage]] in my [[prolapsed anus]] ohhhhh yeessahahahhahaaaaaaaaa, gosh darn my wall is wet, [[John F. Kennedy]] \n| english_release_date = <!-- unspecified since originally published in English -->\n| media_type    = [[Roesmary Kennedy]] got some tittiebaby cum on her private island\n| pages         = \n}}\n'''''My Immortal''''' is a ''[[Harry Potter]]''-based [[fan fiction]] serially published on [[FanFiction.net]] between 2006 and 2007. Known for its incomprehensible narrative and constant digressions, the story centers on a non-canonical female vampire character named \"Ebony Dark'ness Dementia Raven Way\" and her relationships with the characters of the ''Harry Potter'' series, particularly her romantic relationship with [[Draco Malfoy]]. Ultimately, she is prompted by visions to travel back in time to try to defeat the main [[antagonist]] of the series, [[Lord Voldemort]].\n\nSince the beginning of the work's publication, it has gained infamy for its awful writing, plot inconsistency and complete disregard for the original ''Harry Potter'' source material. Often regarded as among the worst fan fiction ever written, ''My Immortal'' is felt to be a detriment to those attempting to bring legitimacy to fan fiction. Despite this, the series has also inspired multiple derivative works, including a [[YouTube]] web series, and is viewed with nostalgia for adolescent fan life.\n\nThe author's identity has never been confirmed and has been deemed by many as \"unsolvable\". The author published the story under the username \"XXXbloodyrists666XXX\" and self-identified as Tara Gilesbie. In September 2017, someone claiming to be the author updated a [[FictionPress]] account stating that she had created an active [[Tumblr]] account under her real name; an effort to locate this Tumblr account resulted in the account of [[Young adult fiction|young adult]] novelist Rose Christo. She has since stated that she was one of two co-authors of ''My Immortal'' and had provided evidence of her authorship to [[Macmillan Publishers]], but controversy that same month over factual errors in her then-forthcoming memoirs has led to doubt as to her authorship.\n\nThe story has been speculated to be a hoax designed to [[Internet troll|troll]] readers and/or to [[Satire|satirize]] fan fiction, but the work and the alleged online presence of the author has also been described as too elaborate and too time-consuming to fake effectively. In September 2017, Christo stated that ''My Immortal'' is a work of satire, though any evidence of this is tied to her own claims of authorship.\n\n==Background and publication==\nThe work was published to [[FanFiction.Net]] between early 2006 and 2007, ultimately totaling 44 chapters and nearly 22,700 words.<ref name=\"Vulture\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2015/03/bizarre-unsolved-mystery-of-my-immortal.html|title=The Bizarre, Unsolved Mystery of 'My Immortal,' the World's Worst Fanfiction Story|last=Riesman|first=Abraham|date=March 12, 2015|publisher=[[Vulture.com]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151125172838/http://www.vulture.com/2015/03/bizarre-unsolved-mystery-of-my-immortal.html|archivedate=November 25, 2015|url-status=live|accessdate=November 28, 2015}}</ref> The forty-fourth chapter was accompanied by an author's note explaining that the author was leaving \"{{sic|dubya}}\", commonly believed to be [[Dubai]], and the chapter would be the last until the author's return.<ref name=\"Vulture\" /><ref name=\"TheVerge\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2013/12/10/5166462/the-worst-thing-ever-written-a-history-of-trollfic|title=The Worst Thing Ever Written|last=Robertson|first=Adi|date=December 10, 2013|website=[[The Verge]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151202084919/http://www.theverge.com/2013/12/10/5166462/the-worst-thing-ever-written-a-history-of-trollfic|archivedate=December 2, 2015|url-status=live|accessdate=November 28, 2015}}</ref> However, no further chapters were published. It was removed by site administrators in 2008, a few months after its last chapter was published. However, it survives in [[Cut, copy, and paste|copied-and-pasted]] versions across the Internet.<ref name=\"Vulture\" /> The work apparently takes its name from the song \"[[My Immortal]]\" by [[Evanescence]].<ref name=\"TheVerge\" /><ref name=\"DailyDot\">{{cite news|url=http://www.dailydot.com/fandom/worst-harry-potter-fanfic-my-immortal-web-series/|title=The worst \"Harry Potter\" fanfic ever is now a hilarious webseries|last=Baker-Whitelaw|first=Gavia|date=July 29, 2013|work=[[The Daily Dot]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160612122150/http://www.dailydot.com/fandom/worst-harry-potter-fanfic-my-immortal-web-series/|archivedate=June 12, 2016|url-status=live|access-date=June 12, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Plot summary==\nThe [[protagonist]] of the story is Ebony{{#tag:ref|Occasionally written therein as ''Enoby, Eboby, Evony, Ebory, Enobby, Enopby, Egogy, Tara,'' or ''TaEbory''.|group=\"note\"}} Dark'ness Dementia Raven Way, a seventeen-year-old [[vampire]] who attends [[Hogwarts]] (located in [[England]] instead of the original books' [[Scotland]]) as a member of [[Slytherin|Slytherin House]]. Hogwarts is depicted as being divided between two [[clique]]s, the \"[[Goth subculture|goffs]]\" and the [[Preppy|preps]]. Ebony and all the [[sympathetic character]]s are part of the goth clique while the members of the prep clique are portrayed unsympathetically. Many of the main characters of ''Harry Potter'' are given {{Sic|\"goffik\"}}  makeovers, moved to the Slytherin House, and renamed.\n\nThe story begins by focusing on Ebony entering a relationship with [[Draco Malfoy]], who is depicted as shy, sensitive and [[bisexuality|bisexual]]. Draco invites Ebony to a [[Good Charlotte]] concert in Hogsmeade. She agrees, and they fly to Hogsmeade together in Draco's flying car. After the concert, they do not go back to the castle, but instead have intercourse in the [[Hogwarts|Forbidden Forest]], but are witnessed by Hogwarts' principal [[Albus Dumbledore]] (often referred to as \"Albert Dumblydore\"), who yells at them and derides them as {{Sic|\"motherfukers\"}}. Later, after learning that Draco used to date [[Harry Potter (character)|Harry \"Vampire\" Potter]] (a nickname he gained because he \"love[s] the taste of human blood\"), Ebony becomes so angry that she runs crying into the Forbidden Forest, where she meets [[Lord Voldemort]]. Voldemort, speaking in faux-archaic English (unlike his teenaged self from the 80s), gives her a gun and demands that she kill \"Vampire\" Potter or else he will kill Draco, but Ebony refuses. Later on, Draco learns of this encounter and he is so angry that Ebony kept it from him that he commits [[suicide]] by [[self-harm|slitting his wrists]].\n\nIn a subsequent scene, however, Vampire has a [[vision (spirituality)|vision]] of Draco being held prisoner by Voldemort. The discrepancy between this and the earlier depiction of Draco having committed suicide is not explained, though it is possibly an intentional plot twist, as prior setup suggests Draco could not die in the manner described. It should also be noted that Ebony herself attempts suicide by slitting her wrists several times throughout the story, but it seems to have no negative effects on her. After rescuing Draco from Voldemort, Ebony and her friends attend a [[My Chemical Romance]] concert in [[Places in Harry Potter#Hogsmeade|Hogsmeade]]. After some songs have been played, the concert ends abruptly when the members of My Chemical Romance reveal themselves to be Voldemort and his [[Death Eater]]s. Voldemort, who had been disguised as lead vocalist [[Gerard Way]] (the inspiration for Ebony's last name), proclaims his intent to kill Ebony and Draco for the former's failure to kill Vampire, but they are saved by Albus Dumbledore, who has just given himself a gothic makeover. The next day, Dumbledore gives a gothic makeover to the Hogwarts Great Hall as well, but Ebony feels that he is a [[poseur]] and dislikes him greatly, a sentiment shared by her friends.\n\nDuring this time, [[Death Eater#Lucius Malfoy|Lucius Malfoy]] and [[Order of the Phoenix (fictional organisation)#Sirius Black|Sirius Black]] are inexplicably shot by a gun-toting \"black guy\" (likely meant to be [[Blade (comics)|Blade]] given the vampire themes). There is also a secondary plot point in which [[Professor Trelawney]] (\"Trevolry\") / [[Professor Sinistra]] (\"Sinister\", \"Sinatra\"), combined into one character, has an addiction to what is presumably the truth serum [[Veritaserum]]. A third plot point sees [[Hogwarts staff#Minerva McGonagall|Professor McGonagall]] (often referred to as \"Mc[[Google]]\" or \"McGoggles\") and [[Severus Snape]] (often called \"Snap\", or \"Snope\" at times) attempting to rape or harm the protagonists. Yet another plot point follows [[Order of the Phoenix (fictional organisation)#Remus Lupin|Remus Lupin]] and Snape being bisexuals who spy on Ebony, at one point resulting in a moment shortly after Draco's \"death\" where they are sitting on their broomsticks with \"Loopin {{Sic|[[Masturbation|masticating]]}}\" to Ebony bathing, to which she responds with shooting them \"a gazillion times\". In addition, [[Rubeus Hagrid|Hagrid]] is inexplicably a teenaged Hogwarts student who has a crush on Ebony, and who is also a Satanist. He visits Ebony in the nurse's office, where she is recovering from slitting her wrists, and bestows upon her a bouquet of pink roses, which he turns into a black flame, as to prove he's not a prep.\n\nEbony begins having mysterious visions, to which she confronts Professor Sinister. After gazing into a black crystal ball, she is told she must [[time travel|travel back in time]] (using a [[pensieve]]) to stop Tom Riddle from becoming Voldemort by seducing him, and to retrieve a cure for Sinister/Trevolry's addiction to \"Volxemortserum\". Arriving in the past, she meets the young Riddle, who calls himself \"[[Satan]]\", and who has been mistakenly referred to as \"[[Neo (The Matrix)|Tom Anderson]]\", \"[[Tom Bombadil]]\", and \"Stan\". \"Satan\" is in a band with [[James Potter (character)|James Potter]], Severus Snape, Sirius Black, and [[Lucius Malfoy]]. He is uncanonically depicted attending Hogwarts at the same time as the Marauders in what is further uncanonically portrayed as the 1980s. The author points out a few [[anachronism]]s in these scenes, telling readers to ignore them. There is also an unexplained cameo by a gothic [[Marty McFly]], who gives Ebony a black [[DeLorean time machine]] able to transform into an [[iPod]], allowing her to travel forward in time.\n\nEventually, Ebony brings \"Satan\" forward in time, where he morphs into the present-day Voldemort. This leads to a confrontation between the forces of good and evil in the Great Hall, in which professor Snape threatens to rape Draco if Ebony does not stab Harry/Vampire. The story ends ambiguously with a shootout between Snape and Draco, Snape summoning Voldemort, and Ebony firing off an [[Avada Kedavra]] curse, which is misrepresented as \"[[abracadabra|abra kedabra]]\".\n\n==Style and genre==\n''My Immortal'' is split into 44 chapters. Author's notes, indicated by \"AN\", both precede and are dispersed throughout the narrative prose. These notes are written in a largely [[phonetic spelling]] and characterized the author as \"standoffish\". As the work progressed, these author's notes increasingly became \"defensive, impenetrable, and prone to mentioning [[suicide attempt]]s\" and defended the work's poor spelling and deviation from [[Canon (fiction)|canon]] characterization from negative reviewers.<ref name=\"Vulture\" />\n\nAbraham Riesman of [[Vulture.com]] described the prose as having \"awkward rhythm, strange digressions, and stultifyingly [[purple prose]]\" and noted that the work is \"agonizing\" to a regular fan fiction reader because of \"all the hated [[Trope (literature)|tropes]]\" it employs in the opening passage alone.<ref name=\"Vulture\" /> Adi Robertson of ''[[The Verge]]'' observed that the quality of the prose declined after the twelfth chapter, when the work's editor had a falling out with the author and became temporarily uninvolved with the work; even after the editor and author reconciled, Robertson felt that the prose \"never recovered\".<ref name=\"TheVerge\" /> Gavia Baker-Whitelaw of ''[[The Daily Dot]]'' noted the work \"featured all the hallmarks of terrible fanfic: hundreds of grammar and spelling mistakes, a nonsensical storyline, and a [[Mary Sue]] protagonist who was clearly a glorified version of the author\" and pointed out the numerous descriptions of the protagonist's [[Hot Topic]] outfits.<ref name=\"DailyDot\" />\n\nThe work is characterized by misspellings permeating both the work itself and the author's notes, to the point that the names of the protagonist and canonical ''Harry Potter'' characters are frequently and variously misspelled.<ref name=\"Vulture\" /><ref name=\"DailyDot\" />\n\nThe work has also been noted to fail to adhere to ''Harry Potter'' canon. It features \"an incredibly OOC&nbsp;[out-of-character] ''Harry Potter''&nbsp;universe\"<ref name=\"TheMarySue\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.themarysue.com/my-immortal-webseries/|title=Infamously Bad ''Harry Potter'' Fanfic ''My Immortal'' Gets Web Series|last=Jaffe|first=Brooke|date=July 29, 2013|publisher=[[The Mary Sue]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160713124934/http://www.themarysue.com/my-immortal-webseries/|archivedate=July 13, 2016|url-status=live|access-date=June 12, 2016}}</ref> where \"at no point do any of the ''Harry Potter'' characters act even slightly like themselves\".<ref name=\"io9\">{{Cite web|url=http://io9.gizmodo.com/the-most-infamously-awful-fanfic-ever-my-immortal-h-961749327|title=The most infamously awful fanfic ever, \"My Immortal,\" has a web series|last=Bricken|first=Rob|date=July 30, 2013|publisher=[[io9]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160616021429/http://io9.gizmodo.com/the-most-infamously-awful-fanfic-ever-my-immortal-h-961749327|archivedate=June 16, 2016|url-status=live|access-date=June 12, 2016}}</ref> References to \"decidedly un-Harry Potterish bands\" such as [[My Chemical Romance]] have also been noted.<ref name=\"DailyDot\" />\n\nChapters 39 and 40, according to the author's notes, were written by a hacker, and the writing in both chapters was a \"much more controlled prose that read like a lampoon of the previous 38\".<ref name=\"Vulture\" />\n\n==Authorship==\n===2006\u20132016: Speculation on authorship and genre===\n''My Immortal'' was published under the username \"XXXbloodyrists666XXX\", and the author also used the name \"Tara Gilesbie\". Author's notes in the story identified a friend nicknamed Raven, operating under the username \"bloodytearz666\", as the work's editor and [[beta reader]]. Later author's notes claimed that someone hacked into Gilesbie's account and wrote chapters 39 and 40.<ref name=\"Vulture\" />\n\nThe true identity of the author became subject to wide speculation, and since the publication of the final chapter, various individuals have claimed to have written the work in jest or as a hoax.<ref name=\"Vulture\" /> Due to its \"systematically terrible\" quality, the work is often believed to be a [[satire]] or [[parody]] of fan fiction.<ref name=\"Vulture\" /><ref name=\"DailyDot\" />\n\nAt the same time, the \"exceedingly complicated\" details of the work, including a series of related online accounts outside of FanFiction.net and the effort of writing a work of such length, led to a \"consensus\" among users of [[Encyclopedia Dramatica]] \u2014 a website notorious for online trolling and dedicated to cataloging \"internet culture\" \u2014 that it would be too difficult to fake and that Gilesbie was writing sincerely, a sentiment apparently shared by other online communities who mocked the author.<ref name=\"Vulture\" /> [[Brad Kim]], editor of [[Know Your Meme]], supported the work as genuine, citing his experiences with writing workshops on [[LiveJournal]] and [[Xanga]] where he encountered similar works, as \"these were the kinds of things that would be formulated by a high-school teenager in the early 2000s\".<ref name=\"Vulture\" /> Writing for [[Vulture.com]], Abraham Riesman wrote that \"[t]he mystery of the authorship of 'My Immortal' \u2014 even in this privacy-averse age \u2014 appears unsolvable.\"<ref name=\"Vulture\" />\n\nA series of videos were uploaded to a [[YouTube]] account named ''xXblo0dyxkissxX'' in 2008 and 2009, with their most recent video being uploaded in 2016,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SJWq0j9vfGc|title=Guess Who's Back?|date=15 January 2016}}</ref> in which two [[goth (subculture)|goths]] named Tara and Raven discuss their lives. The overlap with the culture and style of ''My Immortal'' have led to speculation that these women are the Tara and Raven of the fanfic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2015/03/bizarre-unsolved-mystery-of-my-immortal.html|title=The Bizarre, Unsolved Mystery of \u2018My Immortal,\u2019 the World\u2019s Worst Fanfiction Story|website=Vulture}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://metro.co.uk/2014/09/25/raven-and-tara-perfectly-encapsulate-what-teenage-awkwardness-felt-like-in-the-noughties-4881722/|title=Raven and Tara encapsulate what teenage awkwardness felt like in the noughties|date=25 September 2014|publisher=}}</ref> The two were tracked down by Ethan Chiel in 2014, but claimed not to know anything about ''My Immortal''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wnyc.org/story/goth-teens-internet-are-never-what-they-seem/|title=Goth Teens On The Internet Are Never What They Seem - On the Media|website=WNYC}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://dangerousminds.net/comments/god_save_the_teens_the_insane_youtbe_channel_of_mall_goths_raven_and_tara|title=God save the teens: the insane YouTube channel of mall goths Raven and Tara|date=9 June 2014|website=DangerousMinds}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mediafactory.org.au/hannah-tepoorten/2016/04/09/who-do-you-think-i-am-mr-bubbles9560/|title=Who do you think I am, Mr.Bubbles9560?|website=www.mediafactory.org.au}}</ref>\n\n===2017: Rose Christo co-authorship claim===\nRose Christo, author of [[Young adult fiction|young adult novels]], began writing a memoir about her alleged experiences as a [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]] child in the New York [[Foster care in the United States|foster care system]] titled ''Under the Same Stars: the Search for my Brother and the True Story of My Immortal''. The memoir details the period of time during which she allegedly co-wrote ''My Immortal''. [[Macmillan Publishers]] allegedly hired a lawyer to verify Christo's claims over the course of three days; she claimed to have provided proof through the email address with which she created the FanFiction.net account and a [[USB flash drive|flash drive]] containing the first eleven unedited chapters of ''My Immortal''.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" />\n\nIn March 2017, Christo quietly stated on her [[Tumblr]] account that she co-wrote ''My Immortal''; however, the post gained little notice. In early August 2017, Christo posted an update to a previously unknown FictionPress account seemingly related to Tara Gilesbie that similarly received little attention.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/culture/2017/9/13/16275802/who-wrote-my-immortal-tara-rose-christo|title=My Immortal: solving the mystery of the internet's most beloved \u2014 and notorious \u2014 fanfic|last=Romano|first=Aja|date=September 13, 2017|website=[[Vox (website)|Vox]]|access-date=September 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\nLater in August, an [[Self-publishing|independently published]] ''[[Handbook for Mortals]]'' came to public attention after it was discovered that its sales were artificially inflated to push it to the top of the young adult [[The New York Times Best Seller list|''New York Times'' Best Seller list]], from which it was subsequently removed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/books/la-et-jc-handbook-for-mortals-bestseller-ya-20170824-story.html|title=Did a YA book buy its way to the top of the New York Times bestseller list?|work=LA Times|author=Jessica Roy|date=August 24, 2017|accessdate=August 25, 2017}}</ref><ref name=Italie>{{cite news|last=Italie|first=Hillel|title=Book Pulled From Best-Seller List|url=http://time.com/4917209/ny-times-best-seller-handbook-for-mortals/|accessdate=September 11, 2017|work=Time|agency=Associated Press|date=August 26, 2017}}</ref> Writing similarities between the novel and ''My Immortal'' led to speculation that ''Handbook for Mortals'' author [[Lani Sarem]] was the author of ''My Immortal''. Christo again updated the FictionPress account to say she was not Sarem. She also posted on FictionPress to state that her only social media account was on Tumblr, which operated under her real name.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.dailydot.com/parsec/my-immortal-fanfic-2017-update/|title=Did the mysterious fanfic author behind 'My Immortal' just resurface?|last=Baker-Whitelaw|first=Gavia|date=August 31, 2017|work=[[The Daily Dot]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170831214232/https://www.dailydot.com/parsec/my-immortal-fanfic-2017-update/|archive-date=2017-08-31|url-status=live|access-date=August 31, 2017}}</ref> An editorial assistant at Macmillan Publishers also stated that Sarem was not the author of ''My Immortal'' and stated that Macmillan was to publish the author's memoir.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":4\" />\n\nThese statements sparked a search for the claimed Tumblr account, which was found as Christo's in early September. By September 5, Christo stated on her Tumblr account that she co-wrote ''My Immortal'' and that she had provided proof to her publisher [[Macmillan Publishers (United States)|Macmillan Publishers]], later reported by [[BuzzFeed]],<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/alannabennett/my-immortal-author-hi-vampire|title=People Think They Have The Answer To The Decade-Long Mystery Of Who Wrote \"My Immortal\"|last=Bennett|first=Alanna|date=September 5, 2017|website=|publisher=[[Buzzfeed]]|access-date=September 7, 2017}}</ref> and on September 7, BuzzFeed published her first official statement as the alleged author of ''My Immortal.''<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/alannabennett/exclusive-first-look-under-same-stars-my-immortal-memoir|title=The Story Of \"My Immortal\" Is More Wild And Heartbreaking Than You Imagined|last=Bennett|first=Alanna|date=September 7, 2017|website=|publisher=[[Buzzfeed]]|access-date=September 7, 2017}}</ref> She said of her decision to publicly identify herself as a co-author: \"I would never have come forward about ''My&nbsp;Immortal'' if not for the fact that it coincided with the things that happened to me as a teen.\"<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nLater that month, a forum post on [[Kiwi Farms]] by Christo's brother (the subject of her memoir), verified as such by the forum operators, refuted several of Christo's claims in the upcoming memoir, including those of their ancestry and shared childhood history.<ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.hypable.com/my-immortal-and-5-unanswered-burning-questions/|title=The 'My Immortal' mystery grows: Five new questions after the memoir's cancellation|last=Bryne-Cristiano|first=Laura|date=October 5, 2017|website=|publisher=Hypable|access-date=October 6, 2017}}</ref> The memoir was subsequently canceled by Macmillan after an investigation found factual errors in her narrative; Christo stated that these errors had been purposefully made in an attempt to protect her family's identity.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/jarrylee/the-my-immortal-book-is-no-longer-going-to-be-published|title=The \"My Immortal\" Book Is No Longer Going To Be Published|last=Lee|first=Jarry|date=October 3, 2017|website=|publisher=[[Buzzfeed]]|access-date=October 5, 2017}}</ref> Christo's brother has additionally said that he does not know if Christo wrote ''My Immortal'' and that she enjoyed ridiculing badly written fan fiction.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://moviepilot.com/p/brother-of-my-immortal-author-casts-serious-doubt-on-her-claims/4383046|title=The Author Of 'My Immortal' Is A Fake And I Don't Know What To Believe Anymore|last=Tremeer|first=Eleanor|date=October 5, 2017|website=Movie Pilot|access-date=October 5, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171005185457/https://moviepilot.com/p/brother-of-my-immortal-author-casts-serious-doubt-on-her-claims/4383046|archive-date=October 5, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\":6\" /> Christo confirmed via Tumblr in October that her original name was Theresa Rose Christodoulopoulos, confirmed her brother's identity, conceded to many of his revelations about her, but also disagreed with a few of his claims and reiterated her claim that she was one of the authors of ''My Immortal''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rosechristo1.tumblr.com/post/166154457119/hey-guys-im-still-around-so-it-looks-like-a-few|title=kamakisikaw - Rose Christo's Tumblr account|last=Christo|first=Rose|date=October 7, 2017|website=[[Tumblr]]|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6u2t5THqM?url=https://rosechristo1.tumblr.com/post/166154457119/hey-guys-im-still-around-so-it-looks-like-a-few|archive-date=2017-10-07|url-status=dead|access-date=October 7, 2017}}</ref> She closed the Tumblr account a few days later. ''[[Vox (website)|Vox]]'' described Christo's authorship claim as one of the more likely claims she has made, though still in some doubt.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/culture/2017/10/9/16428248/my-immortal-still-a-mystery-rose-christo-fake|last=Romano|first=Aja|title=The My Immortal memoir has been canceled, and the mystery of the notorious fanfic deepens|date=9 October 2017|accessdate=9 October 2017|website=[[Vox (website)|Vox]]}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n{{Expand section|date=July 2016}}\nBefore its removal from FanFiction.Net, ''My Immortal'' allegedly gained between 8,000<ref name=\"TheVerge\" /><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=The Ultimate Guide to the Harry Potter Fandom|last=Payne|first=E.A.|publisher=Rowan Tree Books|year=2011|isbn=978-0615714912|location=|pages=141}}</ref> to 10,000<ref name=\"Vulture\" /> reviews per posted chapter, most of which were negative and contained [[Flaming (Internet)|flaming]].<ref name=\"TheVerge\"/><ref name=\":0\" /> The quality of the writing and the author's apparent [[Goth subculture|goth]] lifestyle also drew attacks and mockery from users on [[Encyclopedia Dramatica]], [[TV Tropes]], [[LiveJournal]], [[Something Awful]], [[YTMND]] and [[YouTube]].<ref name=\"Vulture\" />\n\nRob Bricken of [[io9]] described the work as a \"masterpiece of weirdness\" and a \"masterpiece of literary disaster\".<ref name=\"io9\"/> Mathilda Gregory of [[BuzzFeed]] called ''My Immortal'' a \"work of comic genius\" that is \"oddly touching.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/mathildia/he-put-his-boys-thingy-in-mine|title=The Gloriously Immortal Life of \"My Immortal\"|last=Gregory|first=Mathilda|date=February 19, 2016|publisher=[[BuzzFeed]]|accessdate=August 20, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160916070128/https://www.buzzfeed.com/mathildia/he-put-his-boys-thingy-in-mine|archivedate=September 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Legacy===\nThe work is often cited as the worst fan fiction ever written<ref name=\"Vulture\"/><ref name=\"TheVerge\" /><ref name=\"TheMarySue\"/> or at least a \"strong contender\" for the title.<ref name=\"DailyDot\"/> The work is considered \"iconic\" not only within the [[Harry Potter fandom|''Harry Potter'' fandom]] but also within the larger fan fiction community.<ref name=\"DailyDot\" /><ref name=\"TheMarySue\" />\n\nThe infamy of the work is considered a \"constant millstone around the necks of fanfiction enthusiasts who struggle to bring legitimacy to the genre\".<ref name=\"Vulture\" /> Christo claimed in September 2017 that ''My Immortal'' is a work of satire, though any evidence of this is tied to her own claims of authorship.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2017/09/my-immortal-rose-christo-under-the-same-stars.html|title=Alleged Author of Legendarily Bad Fanfic 'My Immortal' Steps Forward, Announces Book Deal|last=Reisman|first=Abraham|date=September 7, 2017|publisher=[[Vulture (website) |Vulture]]|access-date=September 11, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Derivative works===\n''My Immortal'' inspired further [[fan work]]s, including [[fan art]] and further fan fiction. It was the subject of numerous [[YouTube]] [[dramatic reading]]s intending to mock the work,<ref name=\"Vulture\"/> and it later inspired a fifteen-episode web series satirizing the work.<ref name=\"Vulture\" /><ref name=\"DailyDot\" />\n\n==See also==\n* ''[[The Eye of Argon]]'', a 1970 published novella with a similar reputation\n* [[Poe's law]], an online adage stating that it is difficult to distinguish authentic works from satire\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=\"note\"}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:''My Immortal'' (fan fiction)}}\n{{Harry Potter}}\n[[Category:2006 short stories]]\n[[Category:2007 short stories]]\n[[Category:Goth subculture]]\n[[Category:Harry Potter fan fiction]]\n[[Category:Internet memes]]\n[[Category:Literature about time travel]]\n[[Category:Literature first published in serial form]]\n[[Category:Mental illness in fiction]]\n[[Category:Outsider literature]]\n[[Category:Satanism in popular culture]]\n[[Category:Suicide in fiction]]\n[[Category:Unfinished creative works]]\n[[Category:Vampires in written fiction]]\n[[Category:Works about depression]]\n[[Category:Works based on Harry Potter]]\n[[Category:Works of uncertain authorship]]\n[[Category:Works of unknown authorship]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{Tone|date=April 2020}}\n{{POV|date=April 2020}}\n}}\n{{Infobox book\n| name          = My Immortal [[Columbine High School Massacre]]\n| title_orig    = \n| translator    = [[Adolf Hitler]]\n| image         = \n| caption = \n| author        = \"XXXbloodyrists666XXX\" (Cedric the Entertainer)\n| country       = \n| language      = English\n| series        = ''[[Harry Potter]]'' {{small|(non-canonical fan fiction)}}\n| genre         = [[Fantasy literature|Fantasy]], [[drama]], [[young adult fiction]]\n| publisher     = \n| release_date  = 2006\u20132007\n| english_release_date = <!-- unspecified since originally published in English -->\n| media_type    = [[Fan fiction]]\n| pages         = \n}}\n'''''My Immortal''''' is a ''[[Harry Potter]]''-based [[fan fiction]] serially published on [[FanFiction.net]] between 2006 and 2007. Known for its incomprehensible narrative and constant digressions, the story centers on a non-canonical female vampire character named \"Ebony Dark'ness Dementia Raven Way\" and her relationships with the characters of the ''Harry Potter'' series, particularly her romantic relationship with [[Draco Malfoy]]. Ultimately, she is prompted by visions to travel back in time to try to defeat the main [[antagonist]] of the series, [[Lord Voldemort]].\n\nSince the beginning of the work's publication, it has gained infamy for its awful writing, plot inconsistency and complete disregard for the original ''Harry Potter'' source material. Often regarded as among the worst fan fiction ever written, ''My Immortal'' is felt to be a detriment to those attempting to bring legitimacy to fan fiction. Despite this, the series has also inspired multiple derivative works, including a [[YouTube]] web series, and is viewed with nostalgia for adolescent fan life.\n\nThe author's identity has never been confirmed and has been deemed by many as \"unsolvable\". The author published the story under the username \"XXXbloodyrists666XXX\" and self-identified as Tara Gilesbie. In September 2017, someone claiming to be the author updated a [[FictionPress]] account stating that she had created an active [[Tumblr]] account under her real name; an effort to locate this Tumblr account resulted in the account of [[Young adult fiction|young adult]] novelist Rose Christo. She has since stated that she was one of two co-authors of ''My Immortal'' and had provided evidence of her authorship to [[Macmillan Publishers]], but controversy that same month over factual errors in her then-forthcoming memoirs has led to doubt as to her authorship.\n\nThe story has been speculated to be a hoax designed to [[Internet troll|troll]] readers and/or to [[Satire|satirize]] fan fiction, but the work and the alleged online presence of the author has also been described as too elaborate and too time-consuming to fake effectively. In September 2017, Christo stated that ''My Immortal'' is a work of satire, though any evidence of this is tied to her own claims of authorship.\n\n==Background and publication==\nThe work was published to [[FanFiction.Net]] between early 2006 and 2007, ultimately totaling 44 chapters and nearly 22,700 words.<ref name=\"Vulture\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2015/03/bizarre-unsolved-mystery-of-my-immortal.html|title=The Bizarre, Unsolved Mystery of 'My Immortal,' the World's Worst Fanfiction Story|last=Riesman|first=Abraham|date=March 12, 2015|publisher=[[Vulture.com]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151125172838/http://www.vulture.com/2015/03/bizarre-unsolved-mystery-of-my-immortal.html|archivedate=November 25, 2015|url-status=live|accessdate=November 28, 2015}}</ref> The forty-fourth chapter was accompanied by an author's note explaining that the author was leaving \"{{sic|dubya}}\", commonly believed to be [[Dubai]], and the chapter would be the last until the author's return.<ref name=\"Vulture\" /><ref name=\"TheVerge\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2013/12/10/5166462/the-worst-thing-ever-written-a-history-of-trollfic|title=The Worst Thing Ever Written|last=Robertson|first=Adi|date=December 10, 2013|website=[[The Verge]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151202084919/http://www.theverge.com/2013/12/10/5166462/the-worst-thing-ever-written-a-history-of-trollfic|archivedate=December 2, 2015|url-status=live|accessdate=November 28, 2015}}</ref> However, no further chapters were published. It was removed by site administrators in 2008, a few months after its last chapter was published. However, it survives in [[Cut, copy, and paste|copied-and-pasted]] versions across the Internet.<ref name=\"Vulture\" /> The work apparently takes its name from the song \"[[My Immortal]]\" by [[Evanescence]].<ref name=\"TheVerge\" /><ref name=\"DailyDot\">{{cite news|url=http://www.dailydot.com/fandom/worst-harry-potter-fanfic-my-immortal-web-series/|title=The worst \"Harry Potter\" fanfic ever is now a hilarious webseries|last=Baker-Whitelaw|first=Gavia|date=July 29, 2013|work=[[The Daily Dot]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160612122150/http://www.dailydot.com/fandom/worst-harry-potter-fanfic-my-immortal-web-series/|archivedate=June 12, 2016|url-status=live|access-date=June 12, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Plot summary==\nThe [[protagonist]] of the story is Ebony{{#tag:ref|Occasionally written therein as ''Enoby, Eboby, Evony, Ebory, Enobby, Enopby, Egogy, Tara,'' or ''TaEbory''.|group=\"note\"}} Dark'ness Dementia Raven Way, a seventeen-year-old [[vampire]] who attends [[Hogwarts]] (located in [[England]] instead of the original books' [[Scotland]]) as a member of [[Slytherin|Slytherin House]]. Hogwarts is depicted as being divided between two [[clique]]s, the \"[[Goth subculture|goffs]]\" and the [[Preppy|preps]]. Ebony and all the [[sympathetic character]]s are part of the goth clique while the members of the prep clique are portrayed unsympathetically. Many of the main characters of ''Harry Potter'' are given {{Sic|\"goffik\"}}  makeovers, moved to the Slytherin House, and renamed.\n\nThe story begins by focusing on Ebony entering a relationship with [[Draco Malfoy]], who is depicted as shy, sensitive and [[bisexuality|bisexual]]. Draco invites Ebony to a [[Good Charlotte]] concert in Hogsmeade. She agrees, and they fly to Hogsmeade together in Draco's flying car. After the concert, they do not go back to the castle, but instead have intercourse in the [[Hogwarts|Forbidden Forest]], but are witnessed by Hogwarts' principal [[Albus Dumbledore]] (often referred to as \"Albert Dumblydore\"), who yells at them and derides them as {{Sic|\"motherfukers\"}}. Later, after learning that Draco used to date [[Harry Potter (character)|Harry \"Vampire\" Potter]] (a nickname he gained because he \"love[s] the taste of human blood\"), Ebony becomes so angry that she runs crying into the Forbidden Forest, where she meets [[Lord Voldemort]]. Voldemort, speaking in faux-archaic English (unlike his teenaged self from the 80s), gives her a gun and demands that she kill \"Vampire\" Potter or else he will kill Draco, but Ebony refuses. Later on, Draco learns of this encounter and he is so angry that Ebony kept it from him that he commits [[suicide]] by [[self-harm|slitting his wrists]].\n\nIn a subsequent scene, however, Vampire has a [[vision (spirituality)|vision]] of Draco being held prisoner by Voldemort. The discrepancy between this and the earlier depiction of Draco having committed suicide is not explained, though it is possibly an intentional plot twist, as prior setup suggests Draco could not die in the manner described. It should also be noted that Ebony herself attempts suicide by slitting her wrists several times throughout the story, but it seems to have no negative effects on her. After rescuing Draco from Voldemort, Ebony and her friends attend a [[My Chemical Romance]] concert in [[Places in Harry Potter#Hogsmeade|Hogsmeade]]. After some songs have been played, the concert ends abruptly when the members of My Chemical Romance reveal themselves to be Voldemort and his [[Death Eater]]s. Voldemort, who had been disguised as lead vocalist [[Gerard Way]] (the inspiration for Ebony's last name), proclaims his intent to kill Ebony and Draco for the former's failure to kill Vampire, but they are saved by Albus Dumbledore, who has just given himself a gothic makeover. The next day, Dumbledore gives a gothic makeover to the Hogwarts Great Hall as well, but Ebony feels that he is a [[poseur]] and dislikes him greatly, a sentiment shared by her friends.\n\nDuring this time, [[Death Eater#Lucius Malfoy|Lucius Malfoy]] and [[Order of the Phoenix (fictional organisation)#Sirius Black|Sirius Black]] are inexplicably shot by a gun-toting \"black guy\" (likely meant to be [[Blade (comics)|Blade]] given the vampire themes). There is also a secondary plot point in which [[Professor Trelawney]] (\"Trevolry\") / [[Professor Sinistra]] (\"Sinister\", \"Sinatra\"), combined into one character, has an addiction to what is presumably the truth serum [[Veritaserum]]. A third plot point sees [[Hogwarts staff#Minerva McGonagall|Professor McGonagall]] (often referred to as \"Mc[[Google]]\" or \"McGoggles\") and [[Severus Snape]] (often called \"Snap\", or \"Snope\" at times) attempting to rape or harm the protagonists. Yet another plot point follows [[Order of the Phoenix (fictional organisation)#Remus Lupin|Remus Lupin]] and Snape being bisexuals who spy on Ebony, at one point resulting in a moment shortly after Draco's \"death\" where they are sitting on their broomsticks with \"Loopin {{Sic|[[Masturbation|masticating]]}}\" to Ebony bathing, to which she responds with shooting them \"a gazillion times\". In addition, [[Rubeus Hagrid|Hagrid]] is inexplicably a teenaged Hogwarts student who has a crush on Ebony, and who is also a Satanist. He visits Ebony in the nurse's office, where she is recovering from slitting her wrists, and bestows upon her a bouquet of pink roses, which he turns into a black flame, as to prove he's not a prep.\n\nEbony begins having mysterious visions, to which she confronts Professor Sinister. After gazing into a black crystal ball, she is told she must [[time travel|travel back in time]] (using a [[pensieve]]) to stop Tom Riddle from becoming Voldemort by seducing him, and to retrieve a cure for Sinister/Trevolry's addiction to \"Volxemortserum\". Arriving in the past, she meets the young Riddle, who calls himself \"[[Satan]]\", and who has been mistakenly referred to as \"[[Neo (The Matrix)|Tom Anderson]]\", \"[[Tom Bombadil]]\", and \"Stan\". \"Satan\" is in a band with [[James Potter (character)|James Potter]], Severus Snape, Sirius Black, and [[Lucius Malfoy]]. He is uncanonically depicted attending Hogwarts at the same time as the Marauders in what is further uncanonically portrayed as the 1980s. The author points out a few [[anachronism]]s in these scenes, telling readers to ignore them. There is also an unexplained cameo by a gothic [[Marty McFly]], who gives Ebony a black [[DeLorean time machine]] able to transform into an [[iPod]], allowing her to travel forward in time.\n\nEventually, Ebony brings \"Satan\" forward in time, where he morphs into the present-day Voldemort. This leads to a confrontation between the forces of good and evil in the Great Hall, in which professor Snape threatens to rape Draco if Ebony does not stab Harry/Vampire. The story ends ambiguously with a shootout between Snape and Draco, Snape summoning Voldemort, and Ebony firing off an [[Avada Kedavra]] curse, which is misrepresented as \"[[abracadabra|abra kedabra]]\".\n\n==Style and genre==\n''My Immortal'' is split into 44 chapters. Author's notes, indicated by \"AN\", both precede and are dispersed throughout the narrative prose. These notes are written in a largely [[phonetic spelling]] and characterized the author as \"standoffish\". As the work progressed, these author's notes increasingly became \"defensive, impenetrable, and prone to mentioning [[suicide attempt]]s\" and defended the work's poor spelling and deviation from [[Canon (fiction)|canon]] characterization from negative reviewers.<ref name=\"Vulture\" />\n\nAbraham Riesman of [[Vulture.com]] described the prose as having \"awkward rhythm, strange digressions, and stultifyingly [[purple prose]]\" and noted that the work is \"agonizing\" to a regular fan fiction reader because of \"all the hated [[Trope (literature)|tropes]]\" it employs in the opening passage alone.<ref name=\"Vulture\" /> Adi Robertson of ''[[The Verge]]'' observed that the quality of the prose declined after the twelfth chapter, when the work's editor had a falling out with the author and became temporarily uninvolved with the work; even after the editor and author reconciled, Robertson felt that the prose \"never recovered\".<ref name=\"TheVerge\" /> Gavia Baker-Whitelaw of ''[[The Daily Dot]]'' noted the work \"featured all the hallmarks of terrible fanfic: hundreds of grammar and spelling mistakes, a nonsensical storyline, and a [[Mary Sue]] protagonist who was clearly a glorified version of the author\" and pointed out the numerous descriptions of the protagonist's [[Hot Topic]] outfits.<ref name=\"DailyDot\" />\n\nThe work is characterized by misspellings permeating both the work itself and the author's notes, to the point that the names of the protagonist and canonical ''Harry Potter'' characters are frequently and variously misspelled.<ref name=\"Vulture\" /><ref name=\"DailyDot\" />\n\nThe work has also been noted to fail to adhere to ''Harry Potter'' canon. It features \"an incredibly OOC&nbsp;[out-of-character] ''Harry Potter''&nbsp;universe\"<ref name=\"TheMarySue\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.themarysue.com/my-immortal-webseries/|title=Infamously Bad ''Harry Potter'' Fanfic ''My Immortal'' Gets Web Series|last=Jaffe|first=Brooke|date=July 29, 2013|publisher=[[The Mary Sue]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160713124934/http://www.themarysue.com/my-immortal-webseries/|archivedate=July 13, 2016|url-status=live|access-date=June 12, 2016}}</ref> where \"at no point do any of the ''Harry Potter'' characters act even slightly like themselves\".<ref name=\"io9\">{{Cite web|url=http://io9.gizmodo.com/the-most-infamously-awful-fanfic-ever-my-immortal-h-961749327|title=The most infamously awful fanfic ever, \"My Immortal,\" has a web series|last=Bricken|first=Rob|date=July 30, 2013|publisher=[[io9]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160616021429/http://io9.gizmodo.com/the-most-infamously-awful-fanfic-ever-my-immortal-h-961749327|archivedate=June 16, 2016|url-status=live|access-date=June 12, 2016}}</ref> References to \"decidedly un-Harry Potterish bands\" such as [[My Chemical Romance]] have also been noted.<ref name=\"DailyDot\" />\n\nChapters 39 and 40, according to the author's notes, were written by a hacker, and the writing in both chapters was a \"much more controlled prose that read like a lampoon of the previous 38\".<ref name=\"Vulture\" />\n\n==Authorship==\n===2006\u20132016: Speculation on authorship and genre===\n''My Immortal'' was published under the username \"XXXbloodyrists666XXX\", and the author also used the name \"Tara Gilesbie\". Author's notes in the story identified a friend nicknamed Raven, operating under the username \"bloodytearz666\", as the work's editor and [[beta reader]]. Later author's notes claimed that someone hacked into Gilesbie's account and wrote chapters 39 and 40.<ref name=\"Vulture\" />\n\nThe true identity of the author became subject to wide speculation, and since the publication of the final chapter, various individuals have claimed to have written the work in jest or as a hoax.<ref name=\"Vulture\" /> Due to its \"systematically terrible\" quality, the work is often believed to be a [[satire]] or [[parody]] of fan fiction.<ref name=\"Vulture\" /><ref name=\"DailyDot\" />\n\nAt the same time, the \"exceedingly complicated\" details of the work, including a series of related online accounts outside of FanFiction.net and the effort of writing a work of such length, led to a \"consensus\" among users of [[Encyclopedia Dramatica]] \u2014 a website notorious for online trolling and dedicated to cataloging \"internet culture\" \u2014 that it would be too difficult to fake and that Gilesbie was writing sincerely, a sentiment apparently shared by other online communities who mocked the author.<ref name=\"Vulture\" /> [[Brad Kim]], editor of [[Know Your Meme]], supported the work as genuine, citing his experiences with writing workshops on [[LiveJournal]] and [[Xanga]] where he encountered similar works, as \"these were the kinds of things that would be formulated by a high-school teenager in the early 2000s\".<ref name=\"Vulture\" /> Writing for [[Vulture.com]], Abraham Riesman wrote that \"[t]he mystery of the authorship of 'My Immortal' \u2014 even in this privacy-averse age \u2014 appears unsolvable.\"<ref name=\"Vulture\" />\n\nA series of videos were uploaded to a [[YouTube]] account named ''xXblo0dyxkissxX'' in 2008 and 2009, with their most recent video being uploaded in 2016,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SJWq0j9vfGc|title=Guess Who's Back?|date=15 January 2016}}</ref> in which two [[goth (subculture)|goths]] named Tara and Raven discuss their lives. The overlap with the culture and style of ''My Immortal'' have led to speculation that these women are the Tara and Raven of the fanfic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2015/03/bizarre-unsolved-mystery-of-my-immortal.html|title=The Bizarre, Unsolved Mystery of \u2018My Immortal,\u2019 the World\u2019s Worst Fanfiction Story|website=Vulture}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://metro.co.uk/2014/09/25/raven-and-tara-perfectly-encapsulate-what-teenage-awkwardness-felt-like-in-the-noughties-4881722/|title=Raven and Tara encapsulate what teenage awkwardness felt like in the noughties|date=25 September 2014|publisher=}}</ref> The two were tracked down by Ethan Chiel in 2014, but claimed not to know anything about ''My Immortal''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wnyc.org/story/goth-teens-internet-are-never-what-they-seem/|title=Goth Teens On The Internet Are Never What They Seem - On the Media|website=WNYC}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://dangerousminds.net/comments/god_save_the_teens_the_insane_youtbe_channel_of_mall_goths_raven_and_tara|title=God save the teens: the insane YouTube channel of mall goths Raven and Tara|date=9 June 2014|website=DangerousMinds}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mediafactory.org.au/hannah-tepoorten/2016/04/09/who-do-you-think-i-am-mr-bubbles9560/|title=Who do you think I am, Mr.Bubbles9560?|website=www.mediafactory.org.au}}</ref>\n\n===2017: Rose Christo co-authorship claim===\nRose Christo, author of [[Young adult fiction|young adult novels]], began writing a memoir about her alleged experiences as a [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]] child in the New York [[Foster care in the United States|foster care system]] titled ''Under the Same Stars: the Search for my Brother and the True Story of My Immortal''. The memoir details the period of time during which she allegedly co-wrote ''My Immortal''. [[Macmillan Publishers]] allegedly hired a lawyer to verify Christo's claims over the course of three days; she claimed to have provided proof through the email address with which she created the FanFiction.net account and a [[USB flash drive|flash drive]] containing the first eleven unedited chapters of ''My Immortal''.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" />\n\nIn March 2017, Christo quietly stated on her [[Tumblr]] account that she co-wrote ''My Immortal''; however, the post gained little notice. In early August 2017, Christo posted an update to a previously unknown FictionPress account seemingly related to Tara Gilesbie that similarly received little attention.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/culture/2017/9/13/16275802/who-wrote-my-immortal-tara-rose-christo|title=My Immortal: solving the mystery of the internet's most beloved \u2014 and notorious \u2014 fanfic|last=Romano|first=Aja|date=September 13, 2017|website=[[Vox (website)|Vox]]|access-date=September 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\nLater in August, an [[Self-publishing|independently published]] ''[[Handbook for Mortals]]'' came to public attention after it was discovered that its sales were artificially inflated to push it to the top of the young adult [[The New York Times Best Seller list|''New York Times'' Best Seller list]], from which it was subsequently removed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/books/la-et-jc-handbook-for-mortals-bestseller-ya-20170824-story.html|title=Did a YA book buy its way to the top of the New York Times bestseller list?|work=LA Times|author=Jessica Roy|date=August 24, 2017|accessdate=August 25, 2017}}</ref><ref name=Italie>{{cite news|last=Italie|first=Hillel|title=Book Pulled From Best-Seller List|url=http://time.com/4917209/ny-times-best-seller-handbook-for-mortals/|accessdate=September 11, 2017|work=Time|agency=Associated Press|date=August 26, 2017}}</ref> Writing similarities between the novel and ''My Immortal'' led to speculation that ''Handbook for Mortals'' author [[Lani Sarem]] was the author of ''My Immortal''. Christo again updated the FictionPress account to say she was not Sarem. She also posted on FictionPress to state that her only social media account was on Tumblr, which operated under her real name.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.dailydot.com/parsec/my-immortal-fanfic-2017-update/|title=Did the mysterious fanfic author behind 'My Immortal' just resurface?|last=Baker-Whitelaw|first=Gavia|date=August 31, 2017|work=[[The Daily Dot]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170831214232/https://www.dailydot.com/parsec/my-immortal-fanfic-2017-update/|archive-date=2017-08-31|url-status=live|access-date=August 31, 2017}}</ref> An editorial assistant at Macmillan Publishers also stated that Sarem was not the author of ''My Immortal'' and stated that Macmillan was to publish the author's memoir.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":4\" />\n\nThese statements sparked a search for the claimed Tumblr account, which was found as Christo's in early September. By September 5, Christo stated on her Tumblr account that she co-wrote ''My Immortal'' and that she had provided proof to her publisher [[Macmillan Publishers (United States)|Macmillan Publishers]], later reported by [[BuzzFeed]],<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/alannabennett/my-immortal-author-hi-vampire|title=People Think They Have The Answer To The Decade-Long Mystery Of Who Wrote \"My Immortal\"|last=Bennett|first=Alanna|date=September 5, 2017|website=|publisher=[[Buzzfeed]]|access-date=September 7, 2017}}</ref> and on September 7, BuzzFeed published her first official statement as the alleged author of ''My Immortal.''<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/alannabennett/exclusive-first-look-under-same-stars-my-immortal-memoir|title=The Story Of \"My Immortal\" Is More Wild And Heartbreaking Than You Imagined|last=Bennett|first=Alanna|date=September 7, 2017|website=|publisher=[[Buzzfeed]]|access-date=September 7, 2017}}</ref> She said of her decision to publicly identify herself as a co-author: \"I would never have come forward about ''My&nbsp;Immortal'' if not for the fact that it coincided with the things that happened to me as a teen.\"<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nLater that month, a forum post on [[Kiwi Farms]] by Christo's brother (the subject of her memoir), verified as such by the forum operators, refuted several of Christo's claims in the upcoming memoir, including those of their ancestry and shared childhood history.<ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.hypable.com/my-immortal-and-5-unanswered-burning-questions/|title=The 'My Immortal' mystery grows: Five new questions after the memoir's cancellation|last=Bryne-Cristiano|first=Laura|date=October 5, 2017|website=|publisher=Hypable|access-date=October 6, 2017}}</ref> The memoir was subsequently canceled by Macmillan after an investigation found factual errors in her narrative; Christo stated that these errors had been purposefully made in an attempt to protect her family's identity.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/jarrylee/the-my-immortal-book-is-no-longer-going-to-be-published|title=The \"My Immortal\" Book Is No Longer Going To Be Published|last=Lee|first=Jarry|date=October 3, 2017|website=|publisher=[[Buzzfeed]]|access-date=October 5, 2017}}</ref> Christo's brother has additionally said that he does not know if Christo wrote ''My Immortal'' and that she enjoyed ridiculing badly written fan fiction.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://moviepilot.com/p/brother-of-my-immortal-author-casts-serious-doubt-on-her-claims/4383046|title=The Author Of 'My Immortal' Is A Fake And I Don't Know What To Believe Anymore|last=Tremeer|first=Eleanor|date=October 5, 2017|website=Movie Pilot|access-date=October 5, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171005185457/https://moviepilot.com/p/brother-of-my-immortal-author-casts-serious-doubt-on-her-claims/4383046|archive-date=October 5, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\":6\" /> Christo confirmed via Tumblr in October that her original name was Theresa Rose Christodoulopoulos, confirmed her brother's identity, conceded to many of his revelations about her, but also disagreed with a few of his claims and reiterated her claim that she was one of the authors of ''My Immortal''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rosechristo1.tumblr.com/post/166154457119/hey-guys-im-still-around-so-it-looks-like-a-few|title=kamakisikaw - Rose Christo's Tumblr account|last=Christo|first=Rose|date=October 7, 2017|website=[[Tumblr]]|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6u2t5THqM?url=https://rosechristo1.tumblr.com/post/166154457119/hey-guys-im-still-around-so-it-looks-like-a-few|archive-date=2017-10-07|url-status=dead|access-date=October 7, 2017}}</ref> She closed the Tumblr account a few days later. ''[[Vox (website)|Vox]]'' described Christo's authorship claim as one of the more likely claims she has made, though still in some doubt.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/culture/2017/10/9/16428248/my-immortal-still-a-mystery-rose-christo-fake|last=Romano|first=Aja|title=The My Immortal memoir has been canceled, and the mystery of the notorious fanfic deepens|date=9 October 2017|accessdate=9 October 2017|website=[[Vox (website)|Vox]]}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n{{Expand section|date=July 2016}}\nBefore its removal from FanFiction.Net, ''My Immortal'' allegedly gained between 8,000<ref name=\"TheVerge\" /><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=The Ultimate Guide to the Harry Potter Fandom|last=Payne|first=E.A.|publisher=Rowan Tree Books|year=2011|isbn=978-0615714912|location=|pages=141}}</ref> to 10,000<ref name=\"Vulture\" /> reviews per posted chapter, most of which were negative and contained [[Flaming (Internet)|flaming]].<ref name=\"TheVerge\"/><ref name=\":0\" /> The quality of the writing and the author's apparent [[Goth subculture|goth]] lifestyle also drew attacks and mockery from users on [[Encyclopedia Dramatica]], [[TV Tropes]], [[LiveJournal]], [[Something Awful]], [[YTMND]] and [[YouTube]].<ref name=\"Vulture\" />\n\nRob Bricken of [[io9]] described the work as a \"masterpiece of weirdness\" and a \"masterpiece of literary disaster\".<ref name=\"io9\"/> Mathilda Gregory of [[BuzzFeed]] called ''My Immortal'' a \"work of comic genius\" that is \"oddly touching.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/mathildia/he-put-his-boys-thingy-in-mine|title=The Gloriously Immortal Life of \"My Immortal\"|last=Gregory|first=Mathilda|date=February 19, 2016|publisher=[[BuzzFeed]]|accessdate=August 20, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160916070128/https://www.buzzfeed.com/mathildia/he-put-his-boys-thingy-in-mine|archivedate=September 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Legacy===\nThe work is often cited as the worst fan fiction ever written<ref name=\"Vulture\"/><ref name=\"TheVerge\" /><ref name=\"TheMarySue\"/> or at least a \"strong contender\" for the title.<ref name=\"DailyDot\"/> The work is considered \"iconic\" not only within the [[Harry Potter fandom|''Harry Potter'' fandom]] but also within the larger fan fiction community.<ref name=\"DailyDot\" /><ref name=\"TheMarySue\" />\n\nThe infamy of the work is considered a \"constant millstone around the necks of fanfiction enthusiasts who struggle to bring legitimacy to the genre\".<ref name=\"Vulture\" /> Christo claimed in September 2017 that ''My Immortal'' is a work of satire, though any evidence of this is tied to her own claims of authorship.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2017/09/my-immortal-rose-christo-under-the-same-stars.html|title=Alleged Author of Legendarily Bad Fanfic 'My Immortal' Steps Forward, Announces Book Deal|last=Reisman|first=Abraham|date=September 7, 2017|publisher=[[Vulture (website) |Vulture]]|access-date=September 11, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Derivative works===\n''My Immortal'' inspired further [[fan work]]s, including [[fan art]] and further fan fiction. It was the subject of numerous [[YouTube]] [[dramatic reading]]s intending to mock the work,<ref name=\"Vulture\"/> and it later inspired a fifteen-episode web series satirizing the work.<ref name=\"Vulture\" /><ref name=\"DailyDot\" />\n\n==See also==\n* ''[[The Eye of Argon]]'', a 1970 published novella with a similar reputation\n* [[Poe's law]], an online adage stating that it is difficult to distinguish authentic works from satire\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=\"note\"}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:''My Immortal'' (fan fiction)}}\n{{Harry Potter}}\n[[Category:2006 short stories]]\n[[Category:2007 short stories]]\n[[Category:Goth subculture]]\n[[Category:Harry Potter fan fiction]]\n[[Category:Internet memes]]\n[[Category:Literature about time travel]]\n[[Category:Literature first published in serial form]]\n[[Category:Mental illness in fiction]]\n[[Category:Outsider literature]]\n[[Category:Satanism in popular culture]]\n[[Category:Suicide in fiction]]\n[[Category:Unfinished creative works]]\n[[Category:Vampires in written fiction]]\n[[Category:Works about depression]]\n[[Category:Works based on Harry Potter]]\n[[Category:Works of uncertain authorship]]\n[[Category:Works of unknown authorship]]\n", "name_user": "2601:5cc:c500:7610:d904:eda7:319e:c77d", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/My_Immortal_(fan_fiction)"}
